SERO PHROST LOOKED down into the grey darkness of the sea below as his aircar swooped back toward Purgatory. No explanation, no apology, just the flat order to turn back--an order his pilot robot was obeying, despite his best efforts to convince it otherwise. The turn-back order came from a traffic safety center, and the First Law saw to it that that was all a robot needed to know in order to force obedience. \par
\tab But why the turn-around? An arrest order? What did they think they knew? And arrested for what? He would have to be careful, very careful. More than one person had been pulled in on a minor charge and made the mistake of assuming it was about some larger matter. \par
\tab Or was it his own arrest that he was flying back toward? Phrost looked out the porthole and saw the running lights of several other aircars heading back to Purgatory. A dragnet? Perhaps, if he permitted himself to grasp at straws, it had nothing to do with him at all. It could be they were acting on a rustbacking tip-off, and pulling back all flights that had left at a certain time. No way to know. Perhaps it had nothing at all to do with him. \par
\tab The guilty flee when no one pursues. Admit nothing,  reveal nothing. There was still every chance for him to win out. \par
\tab The dark sky rushed past him. \par
\par
\tab Alvar Kresh glanced at the wall clock in the operations room. Just before 0700 hours. A bare five hours since he had found the body, though it seemed that enough had happened since then to fill up a month\'92s worth of days. Tierlaw Verick was filed away for future reference, held under close guard in the same room in which he had been questioned, while the Crime Scene robots went over the room in which he had slept. Kresh doubted that Verick had anything to do with the assassination, but hunches were no way to run an investigation. Who knew what they might find, until they looked? \par
\tab Someone had set up a conference table in the ops room, and Kresh, Fredda Leving, and Justen Devray sat at three of its sides, while Donald 111 stood at the fourth. All of them--even Donald, somehow--seemed exhausted, drawn out, the press of events leaving them all far behind the pace. And yet it seemed they were no further ahead than they had been when they had started. \par
\tab The clock was moving, and moving fast. Kresh dared not delay much longer in contacting the key members of the government, or in announcing Grieg\'92s death to all Inferno. \par
\tab But the moment he did that, Kresh knew, all hell would break loose. He could not foresee what form the chaos would take, but he knew, beyond doubt, that there would be chaos. He desperately needed to have much of this investigation under control before the news broke wide. And the damage could only be made worse if the first announcement came from someplace beside Alvar Kresh\'92s own mouth--a probability that was increasing with every second that passed. \par
\tab A deputy might say something over an unscrambled channel that would be overheard, or call a friend or family member with the news, or give or sell the story of the century to a friend in the news business. Or the killers might decide it suited their purposes to make the announcement. Or someone who called Grieg might do what Kresh had done, and realize the Grieg on the other end was a simulation. The sim was still running on the phone system, half to help keep the lid on and half to leave it intact for the analysis teams. \par
\tab They would have to make the announcement soon, very soon, if they were to keep any sort of control over events. But before Kresh told anyone anything, he needed a chance to think, to compare notes, to plan. A council of war--because it might quite literally be that Grieg\'92s death was the opening shot in an actual war. There was no way to know. \par
\tab He was sure Justen Devray understood all that, and it at least seemed as if Fredda Leving did. Kresh found that he was impressed--very impressed--by the way she had handled herself in the midst of all this chaos. There was a lot to admire about the young, smart, and beautiful Fredda Leving. But Kresh did not feel he could rely too much on her instincts when it came to criminal investigation. She had shown in Verick\'92s interrogation that she thought in too straight a line for police work. Maybe the direct approach worked in science, where the facts did not mind being discovered. Police work, on the other hand, was a form of research where the facts were often determined to elude capture. Head straight for them and they\'92d be bound to escape. \par
\tab \'93All right, Donald,\'94 Alvar said. \'93Let\'92s get started. What do we have, and what do we need?\'94 \par
\tab \'93We have ascertained, through Tierlaw Verick\'92s statement, that Caliban and Prospero were almost certainly the last to see Governor Grieg alive,\'94 Donald said. \'93I have placed an all-points bulletin for their capture, but it seems unlikely we will apprehend them quickly--especially if we do not have the full cooperation of the SSS. Neither the Rangers nor our own department have arrest powers here, or facilities for performing inquiries. \par
\tab \'93Neither Prospero nor Caliban are presently available or traceable via hyperwave, and both have duties that require them to be out in the field a great deal. It is possible they are following their normal routines, but are simply out of touch. It is also possible that they have gone into hiding. We will do all we can to trace them, given the limitations of our circumstances. \'94\par
\tab Interesting that Donald would start with the robots, Kresh thought. He was focused, perhaps overfocused, on them. It would be best to keep in mind that in this investigation at least, Donald was not likely to be even remotely as objective as he normally was. Clearly, he wanted Prospero and Caliban to be guilty. A biased robot. As if there weren\'92t enough problems on this case. \par
\tab \'93How reliable is Tierlaw\'92s statement?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93As best I could ascertain, all of his bodily reactions were consistent with a man under great stress giving a truthful statement. I believe that he spoke the truth, \'93 Donald said. \par
\tab And that was the least-qualified pronouncement Donald had ever made concerning his lie-detector function. Enough so that Kresh felt unsure. Usually Donald made a speech three times longer than that about the uncertainty of such measurement. No doubt about it--he wanted the robots to be guilty. \par
\tab \'93We should be able to check his story out against Grieg\'92s appointment diary,\'94 Devray said. \'93That\'92s something. But at least we have a lead, and suspects.\'94\par
\tab \'93Even leaving aside the First Law question, I can\'92t see what possible motive Caliban and Prospero could have for attacking Grieg, or why they would have been so clumsy about it,\'94 Fredda protested. \'93Yes, Caliban has no First Law. In theory, there is nothing to prevent him attacking anyone he likes. But there\'92s nothing preventing me, or you, either. And yes, Prospero\'92s First Law does not enjoin him to prevent harm--but I can\'92t imagine Prospero splitting hair so fine as to interpret that as participating in a murder but not actually firing the weapon--which is what you\'92d have to have here.\'94\par
\tab \'93But you do grant,\'94 Devray said, \'93that there is nothing in Caliban\'92s absence of Laws that would prevent him from killing Grieg? And that there is nothing in the New Laws that would absolutely force Prospero to prevent the attack?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Yes, but--\'94\par
\tab \'93So one of them could kill and the other could stand idly by,\'94 Devray said, his tone a bit badgering. \par
\tab \'93In theory, yes,\'94 Fredda admitted, with massive reluctance. \'93But it makes no sense. Grieg was the best friend the New Law robots ever had. What would make them want to kill him?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Plenty,\'94 Devray said. \'93I have an appointment--had an appointment--with the Governor for later this morning. We were going to talk about a proposal I had submitted last week.\'94\par
\tab \'93What sort of proposal?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93One for the destruction of all New Law robots,\'94 Devray said. \par
\tab \'93What? Have you taken leave of your senses?\'94 Fredda demanded. \par
\tab \'93No, ma\'92am,\'94 Devray replied, his voice bland and professional. \'93But I\'92m damned sick and tired of chasing rustbackers. The N. L. s are at the focus of a whole new series of crimes--rustback smuggling, restrictor removal, and the founding of illegal settlements.\'94\par
\tab \'93Settlements?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93Well, one settlement, anyway,\'94 Devray said. \'93They call it Valhalla. It\'92s supposed to be somewhere on the far side of the planet from here, somewhere in the Utopia region of Terra Grande. I don\'92t even know if it exists--but it\'92s where half the rustbacks we catch seem to be heading. And I\'92m tired of wasting time and effort chasing rumors. I told the Governor the rustbacks and the New Law robots were more trouble than they were worth, and it was time to admit it and move on.\'94\par
\tab \'93But they work!\'94 Fredda protested. \'93New Law robots represent half the work force on Purgatory.\'94 \par
\tab \'93And they were supposed to be all of it--except they\'92re only about a third as productive as Three-Law robots. Every department has been forced to pull in human workers, because the Settlers don\'92t allow Three-Law robots to have the run of the island. If the New Law robots were worth all the trouble they cause, that\'92d be one thing,\'94 Devray said. \'93But if anything, they\'92re slowing down the reterraforming project.\'94 \par
\tab Kresh was surprised to see Devray that interested in terraforming--and then realized he shouldn\'92t have been surprised at all. The Rangers only did law enforcement on the side. Terraforming was much more their side of the street. \par
\tab \'93Was--was the Governor considering the idea?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93I don\'92t know,\'94 Devray said. \'93He didn\'92t reject it out of hand. I know he was also toying with the idea of removing all the range restrictors and letting the New Law robots go.\'94\par
\tab \'93Why the devil would he do that?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93There wouldn\'92t be a New Law left on this island if not for the restrictors.\'94\par
\tab \'93Don\'92t be too sure of that,\'94 Fredda said. \'93A lot of the New Law robots do cause trouble--but the ones that do work, work plenty hard. A lot of the rustbacks work very hard indeed--once they\'92re paid a decent wage. And not all of them head for Valhalla, Justen. And just by the way, Valhalla is no rumor. It\'92s a real place--and there are lots of good reasons for the New Laws to head for it. I\'92ve seen that with my own eyes.\'94\par
\tab \'93You seem to know a lot about rustbacks,\'94 Devray said. \'93And have you reported these escaped robots in Valhalla you\'92ve seen with your own eyes? Or reported Valhalla\'92s location?\'94 \par
\tab \'93No, I have not reported that information,\'94 she snapped. \'93I don\'92t know where Valhalla is, and I don\'92t want to know. But if you want to arrest me for seeing a rustback, go right ahead. I felt responsible for them. Rustbacks are escaped New Law robots, and I invented New Law robots. Of course I\'92d research them.\'94\par
\tab \'93Hold it, both of you,\'94 Kresh said. \'93This is not the time. We can go into all this later. Right now the only important thing is that Devray\'92s recommendation to the Governor could have given Caliban and Prospero a very strong motive if they knew about it. They might have decided to kill him before he killed them.\'94\par
\tab \'93Caliban isn\'92t a New Law robot--\'94\par
\tab \'93Burning hells, I know that better than anyone!\'94 Kresh snapped. \'93But maybe he decided not to take chances on being caught up in a roundup. Or maybe he just acted in sympathy to the plight of his New Law brethren. It\'92s a possible motive, and the two of them are definite suspects.\'94\par
\tab \'93But you can\'92t just decide they did it. Any number of humans might have--\'94 \par
\tab \'93I said they were suspects, not the suspects,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Even if I were convinced they did it--and I\'92m not--I wouldn\'92t dare stop investigating other possibilities. Not until the other shoe drops. Suppose it wasn\'92t the robots? Suppose humans did this job? What was their motive? Have they achieved it with Grieg\'92s death, or is there more to follow? Is it a coup, or a simple assassination?\'94 \par
\tab \'93A coup? Stars above, I hadn\'92t even thought of that,\'94 Fredda said. \par
\tab \'93I haven\'92t thought of much else,\'94 Kresh said. \'93But I\'92ll tell you this--with every minute that passes, it becomes less likely that it was--is--a coup. If you\'92re attempting to overthrow a government, you don\'92t give it time to recover from the first blow before you strike again. Unless something has gone wrong with their plans. Or unless--hellfire, that\'92s a tough one.\'94\par
\tab \'93What\'92s a tough one?\'94 Fredda demanded. \par
\tab \'93Suppose the public announcement of Grieg\'92s death is the signal for their next move?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Well, there\'92s some chance of that,\'94 Devray agreed. \'93I doubt the killers expected the body would be discovered so soon--or that you would discover it. They set up the image box to do the comm simulation, after all. \'94\par
\tab \'93Yes,\'94 Fredda said. \'93Probably the killers weren\'92t expecting discovery until this morning. \'94 She looked up at Kresh and shrugged. \'93Maybe it was Tierlaw who was supposed to find the body. Unless Tierlaw did it and was planning to pretend to discover the body this morning. Except Donald said his monitors showed that Tierlaw was telling the truth.\'94\par
\tab \'93Don\'92t trust Donald\'92s sensors that far,\'94 Kresh said. \'93A trained man could beat his sensors--or any lie-detector system, short of a Psychic Probe. But Tierlaw could have been set up, a useful idiot. \'94\par
\tab \'93How the devil can an idiot be useful?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93By being worse than useless to your opposition. Maybe we\'92re supposed to pay so much attention to Tierlaw that we let the real perpetrators get away. But that\'92s giving them an awful lot of credit, and assumes an incredibly complex and fragile plot. My guess is that the assassins are completely unaware of Tierlaw\'92s existence, and he is telling the precise truth: He had nothing to do with it, and he slept through the whole thing. But don\'92t worry, we\'92re going to hold him and check him out all the same.\'94\par
\tab \'93If you\'92re right,\'94 Devray said, \'93then how was the body supposed to be discovered? The plotters had to have thought about it. What were they expecting?\'94\par
\tab \'93Well,\'94 Fredda said, \'93all the regular household robots had been ordered to clear off to an outbuilding for the night of the party. There are two deputies interviewing them now, but I doubt they\'92ll get anything. They would have returned this morning--right about now, I suppose--to resume their normal duties.\'94\par
\tab \'93So a robot was supposed to discover Grieg was dead,\'94 Kresh said. \'93What would have happened then?\'94 he asked. \par
\tab Fredda thought for a moment. \'93It depends very much on the robot\'92s preexisting and contingency orders, of course, but most likely, all hell would break loose. It would call for help, attempt resuscitation, call for reinforcements, request a security alert, and who knows what else. \'94\par
\tab \'93All the proper things to do in terms of the Three Laws, but that would have set off absolute chaos,\'94 Kresh said. \'93If that had happened, every kind of cop within two hundred kilometers would have been over the Residence, banging into each other and the news media and whatever political leaders managed to get involved. The devil only knows what sort of hell that would have stirred up. And all an attempt to revive Grieg would have accomplished would be the muddling of the evidence. Just the sort of chaos and confusion a coup plotter would want. \'94\par
\tab \'93Maybe,\'94 Devray said. \'93Maybe. There\'92s a lot of guessing in there, but it might be right.\'94\par
\tab \'93Sir,\'94 Donald said, \'93if I may interject, there are other vital issues that must be considered before we establish any sort of motive for other hypothetical suspects.\'94\par
\tab \'93What other issues?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93There is the question of the weapon. \'94\par
\tab \'93Hell\'92s bells, the weapon. I am getting old. \'94\par
\tab \'93What about the weapon?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93There are energy scanners at every entrance to this building,\'94 said Kresh, \'93and perimeter scanners as well. No one should have been able to get an energy weapon into this building without half a dozen alarms going crazy. How did the weapon get in here? How did it get out?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Or did it get out?\'94 Devray asked. \'93Why risk taking it both ways through the scanners? You might set off an alarm on the way out. If I were doing this job, I wouldn\'92t take chances on smuggling the gun in. The building was unoccupied for damn-all long enough to plant a hundred blasters. r d hide a nice standard blaster with a shielded power pack, do the job, and then abandon the blaster on the premises. \'94\par
\tab \'93Hmmph. It\'92s a possibility,\'94 Kresh said. \par
\tab \'93I beg your pardon, Commander Devray, but there is one point that argues against such a possibility,\'94 Donald said. \'93The energy-discharge curve.\'94\par
\tab \'93What\'92s that?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93By examining the Governor\'92s wounds and the blaster damage to the robots, and by establishing range, it was possible to note the relative power of each shot, and thus the weapon\'92s charge level for each shot. For any given blaster, each shot is less and less intense as the blaster\'92s charge is expended. For the weapon in question, the intensity of the blaster shots declined precipitously with each firing, clearly indicating an unusually small power cell. The discharge pattern was quite unlike any of the common makes and models of blaster. \'94\par
\tab \'93And an undersized power cell suggests a weapon intended for concealment, \'93 Kresh said. \'93A custom job. And custom-made weapons can be traced. You\'92re right, Donald, that needs looking into.\'94\par
\tab \'93Yes, sir. I think we must also ask ourselves about the assault on Tonya Welton, and the subsequent arrival of the false SSS agents. Was it indeed some sort of diversion linked to the attack? And if so, who was it supposed to divert, and what was it supposed to divert that person from?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Especially as we established almost immediately that it was bogus,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Why stage a diversion that would make us more suspicious?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Maybe because at that point it didn\'92t matter anymore,\'94 Devray said. \'93Maybe the thing it was supposed to divert attention from wasn\'92t the Governor\'92s death at all. And maybe it wasn\'92t you it was meant to distract.\'94\par
\tab \'93Huthwitz,\'94 Kresh said. \'93The murder of Emoch Huthwitz. You\'92re suggesting that it was sheer chance that it happened the same night as Grieg\'92s murder.\'94\par
\tab \'93It\'92s possible. Maybe the Welton attack was meant to divert the Rangers away from the attack on one of their own. \'94\par
\tab \'93That won\'92t work,\'94 Fredda objected. \'93From what you\'92ve told me, this Huthwitz was found hours after he was killed. No one noticed he was missing. And it doesn\'92t sound like much of anyone in the Rangers responded to the attack on Welton.\'94\par
\tab \'93All good points,\'94 Kresh agreed. \'93But Huthwitz\'92s death doesn\'92t make sense as a coincidence, either.\'94\par
\tab \'93Coincidences never make sense,\'94 Fredda said. \'93They happen by chance, not logic.\'94\par
\tab \'93But there\'92s a point beyond which chance is an awfully weak explanation. In fact, it\'92s always a weak explanation.\'94\par
\tab \'93Well, suppose Huthwitz was the diversion?\'94 asked Fredda. \'93While you were out looking at his body, the Governor was being killed. \'94\par
\tab \'93That doesn\'92t work, either,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Huthwitz was killed hours before the Governor. Our best estimate was he was killed before the attack on Tonya Welton. As for the discovery of his body as a diversion, he could have been discovered hours later or hours before he was. And the Governor had been dead for about an hour before we found Huthwitz. And besides, we just got through agreeing that the plotters intended Grieg to be discovered some time in the morning, hours from now. \'94\par
\tab \'93But it was Huthwitz\'92s death that led you to check on the Governor,\'94 Leving said. \par
\tab \'93But no one could have predicted it would cause me to check, and my discovery of the body didn\'92t do anyone any good,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Beyond all that, if Huthwitz was killed as a diversion, it didn\'92t much matter who they killed. But Commander Devray has as much as told me he thinks someone might have had very good reasons to kill Huthwitz, and Huthwitz alone.\'94\par
\tab \'93So what are you saying?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93I\'92m saying that the two murders are related--but I haven\'92t the faintest idea how. Right now Donald is the only one with a theory of the crime. \'94\par
\tab \'93Sir, I would submit that I have much more than a theory. I have means, motive, and opportunity. I have two suspects.\'94\par
\tab \'93Donald, you want them to be guilty,\'94 Fredda said. \'93If they killed Grieg, it would confirm all your strongest fears about New Law robots. But I\'92m no investigator, and I can see all the holes in the case against them. I agree with Sheriff Kresh that it seems extremely unlikely that Grieg\'92s murder was unrelated to everything else that happened last night. How could Caliban and Prospero have killed Huthwitz--and why would they do it? How and why did they arrange the attack on Tonya and the phony SSS agents that took away her assailants?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I cannot, as yet, answer those questions, Dr. Leving. And despite your objections, they are the only suspects we have.\'94\par
\tab \'93I agree,\'94 Kresh said. \'93We need to bring them in. But we also need to work on finding ourselves some other suspects as well. We\'92re going to have to go over the access recorder records. And we need to get hold of all the video imagery shot by all the news outlets. We need to go over it frame by frame, and if we can spot anything or anyone who shouldn\'92t be there.\'94\par
\tab \'93I can attend to that, Sheriff,\'94 Donald said. \par
\tab \'93Good. \'93 Kresh glanced up at the wall clock again. Time was moving. Moving too damned fast. \'93I need to draft some sort of statement,\'94 he said. \'93We\'92ve waited long enough. We\'92re not going to get things under any more control than they are right now. I have to notify the government, and then the public.\'94\par
\tab He stood up, rubbed his face with a tired hand, and ran his thick, stubby fingers through his white hair. \'93It\'92s time to tell the world that Chanto Grieg is dead. \'94\par
