 \'93OTTLEY BISSAL,\'94 Donald said. A grainy blowup of a still image from the integrator sequence appeared on the left side of the main display screen. A sharp, clear 3-D mug shot image popped into being on the right side. There was no doubt it was the same man. \'93 As Dr. Leving predicted, Bissal did indeed leave a calling card behind, so to speak. \'94\par
\tab Donald was standing by the screen at one end of a conference table, addressing Fredda, Sheriff Kresh, and Commander Devray. About fourteen hours had passed since Kresh had discovered the body, and about three since Fredda had found the destroyed SPR robot in the lowerlevel storage room. \par
\tab Fredda felt utterly exhausted, and knew that no one else was doing much better. Kresh had caught a quick nap, and Devray probably had too. But no one was going to be doing much sleeping for a while. Donald was the only one of them at his best--\par
\tab \'93The Crime Scene robots recovered multiple fingerprints,\'94 Donald went on, \'93along with hairs and flecks of skin, from the interior of one of the storage closets in the room where the security robots were held. It is clear that Bissal secreted himself in that closet for some time--long enough that he shed several hairs and several flecks of dandruff and other dead skin. From these we recovered DNA samples that provided a definitive match with Bissal\'92s employment file. The fingerprint evidence from the door frame of the closet door provided independent corroboration of this identification.\'94\par
\tab \'93All right,\'94 said Justen Devray. \'93The guy in the closet was Ottley Bissal. So who the hell is Ottley Bissal?\'94 \par
\tab \'93That,\'94 said Donald, \'93is the question we have been working to answer since the forensic identity team gave us a name, about half an hour ago. We have made very rapid progress--mainly because every law enforcement service on the planet seems to have had an extensive file on Bissal.\'94\par
\tab \'93Wonderful,\'94 Kresh said. \'93That means everyone is going to wonder why we didn\'92t do anything about him before he killed the Governor. Go on, Donald. What was in the files?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Ottley Bissal,\'94 Donald said, reading off the file. \'93Single, never married, age twenty-seven standard years. Born and raised in a lower-class area of the city of Hades. Limited education. Low general aptitude shown on a number of evaluative tests taken at school. Notations from various schoolteachers and counselors to the effect that he was a disruptive child and a low achiever. Once out of school, he worked various odd jobs with long stretches of nonemployment or nonregistered employment in between. Few known associates or friends. \'94\par
\tab \'93The classic loser-loner, it sounds like,\'94 said Devray. \par
\tab \'93I take it there were a few brushes with the law?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93Yes, sir. Many arrests, some indictments, but only a few convictions. There seem to be two major categories of offense to which he was prone: street brawling and petty theft. He was granted a suspended sentence for his first assault conviction six years ago. Four years ago, he served three months time in the Hades City Jail for theft. \par
\tab \'93As a second-time offender, he was required to obtain employment upon release and hold a job for no less than an accumulated total of five years. With discharges for cause from various jobs, and bouts of unemployment, he has only accumulated three years of employment thus far. His parole officer rates his progress as \'91unsatisfactory. \'92\'94\par
\tab \'93I\'92m not real clear on the business about a job,\'94 Fredda said. \'93How does holding a job make sense as part of punishment for assault?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Well, if you were in law enforcement, it would make a great deal of sense, \'93 Kresh said. \'93The average formal unemployment rate on Inferno is ninety percent. Only ten percent of the population have a full-time occupation for which they receive significant compensation. No one needs to work in order to live, not with robots taking care of us. But there are people--like those of us around this table--who need to work for other, psychological, reasons. Work is what gives people like us satisfaction, or maybe a big part of our reason for being. \par
\tab \'93A fair number of the other ninety percent--say half of them--stay just as busy as we workers do, but are busy with things that might not be considered \'91jobs. \'92 Art, or music, or gardening, or sex. Most-nearly all--of the rest of the unemployed don\'92t really do much of anything but let the robots take care of them. Harmless drones. Maybe they amuse themselves by sleeping a lot, or by shopping, or by watching entertainments or playing games. Maybe they are vaguely discontented. Maybe they\'92re bored and depressed. Maybe they love each and every day of life. No one really knows. I wouldn\'92t want to be one of them, and I don\'92t think much of them--but at least they don\'92t do any harm. \par
\tab \'93But that leaves us with the leftovers. The ones who have no work they love, no consuming interest, and no capacity for accepting passive inactivity. Troublemakers. Mostly male, mostly uneducated, mostly young and restless. Bissal fits the profile of the people who commit--what is it, Donald--ninety-five percent?\'94 \par
\tab \'93That is approximately correct,\'94 Donald said. \par
\tab \'93Close enough. People like Bissal commit ninety-five percent of the violent crime on Inferno. Compared to Settlers, we have very short jail sentences here, for all but the most serious offenses--and leaving a bored troublemaker to rot in jail for years didn\'92t seem to make much sense anyway. So the powers that be remembered a very old saying about idle hands and the devil\'92s playthings, and passed a law. \'94\par
\tab \'93The idea is,\'94 Devray said, \'93if you\'92re forced to have a job, then there is at least a hope that you will become interested enough in the work, or at least be kept busy and made tired enough by it, so you won\'92t be bored and energetic enough to commit fresh crimes. And it works fairly well. People find out that doing something is more satisfying and interesting than being bored and angry. \'94 Devray nodded toward the report Donald was reading. \'93It doesn\'92t sound like it\'92s worked on Bissal, though.\'94\par
\tab \'93Well, yes and no, unfortunately,\'94 Donald said. \par
\tab \'93What do you mean?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93What sort of work did he do when he did work?\'94 \par
\tab \'93At first he held a number of jobs wherein he seems to have done very little work at all--not exactly the intent of the Criminal Employment Act. Most of his jobs seem to have consisted of little more than watching robots do the actual labor. He seems to have been discharged from a number of these positions for absenteeism. Then, for a time, he did jobs that entailed unskilled work unsuitable for a robot.\'94\par
\tab \'93What the hell sort of work is beneath a robot but suited to a human?\'94 Fredda asked. \'93No offense, Donald, but it seems to me Infernals stick robots with all sorts of silly, useless demeaning tasks. I can\'92t imagine anything they wouldn\'92t make a robot do--especially anything that a human would agree to do.\'94\par
\tab \'93Your point is well taken. However, there are a number of unskilled or semi-skilled tasks that are unsuited to robotic labor, mainly because of the First Law. Certain forms of security work, for example. A guard must be able to shoot his gun if need be, and a guard that a thief would have no compunction against shooting would be of limited use. \par
\tab \'93Other jobs would require robots to be so highly specialized in order to meet a job situation that comes up so rarely that it is not worth designing and manufacturing specialized robots for the task. Certain seafaring jobs, such as deep-sea fishing, for example, entail a small risk of falling overboard. Robots sink. It is certainly possible to build robots that float and yet are robust enough to survive salt air and the other hazards of a maritime environment, but it is far easier and cheaper to hire a human and give him or her a life preserver. There are other jobs that would be dangerous to a robot but entail little or no risk for a human.\'94\par
\tab \'93Thank you, Donald, we get the point,\'94 Kresh said. \'93So what line of work did Bissal finally settle into?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Mobile security work,\'94 Donald said, the note of distaste in his mouth unmistakable. \'93 Armed protection of valuable shipments.\'94\par
\tab \'93Oh, hell,\'94 Kresh said. \'93That\'92s perfect. Absolutely perfect. The one sort of job we don\'92t like crooks taking on.\'94\par
\tab \'93Wait a second,\'94 Fredda protested. \'93You\'92ve lost me again. What\'92s so bad about that?\'94 \par
\tab Kresh held up his right hand, his thumb about a centimeter from his index finger. \'93It\'92s about that far from smuggling and contraband running,\'94 he said. \'93Grieg\'92s appropriation of robots gave us a labor shortage and an illicit labor source and a need to find a way to pay for the illicit labor, all rolled into one. Smuggling and contraband are a big part of the means of payment.\'94\par
\tab Devray turned to Donald. \'93This mobile security work Bissal was doing. I realize we\'92re still working with very preliminary information, but is there any likelihood he got mixed up in rustbacking?\'94 \par
\tab \'93There is every likelihood,\'94 Donald said. \'93Indeed, it seems he has only worked for firms on our rustbacking watchlist. \'94\par
\tab \'93One more time,\'94 Fredda said. \'93Sorry, but I just don\'92t know what you\'92re talking about. What\'92s rustbacking got to do with anything?\'94 \par
\tab \'93You weren\'92t around,\'94 Devray said. \'93One of my Rangers picked up a \'91backer on the east coast of the Great Bay. The rustbacker named a Ranger involved in the rustback trade. Huthwitz. The Ranger that got killed.\'94\par
\tab \'93So what?\'94\par
\tab \'93So rustbacking keeps showing up in this case,\'94 Kresh said. \'93 And remember Grieg was considering the idea of get ting rid of the New Law robots. That would have put the rustbackers out of business. Someone in the business would have a terrific motive for killing Grieg before he cut into profits.\'94\par
\tab \'93But wait a second,\'94 Fredda said. \'93I think we have to assume that whoever killed Grieg also killed Huthwitz. Unless we had two killers wandering the Residence that night. \'94\par
\tab \'93Pardon, madame,\'94 Donald said. \'93One slight correction. I think we have to assume the two murders are linked, whether or not the same individual carried them both out. It may be that another member of the same team killed Huthwitz. There is a great deal of evidence of a conspiracy as it is. \'94\par
\tab \'93Even so,\'94 Fredda said. \'93You\'92re talking about the rustbackers plotting to kill Grieg before he could be bad for business. But if Huthwitz was on the take from the \'91backers, why kill him?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Space only knows,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Maybe he was about to talk. Maybe he was demanding too much pay for his silence, and they thought of a way to save some money. Maybe killing Huthwitz wasn\'92t part of the plan, and Bissal was taking care of some of his own personal business on company time. If you think one smuggler wouldn\'92t kill another just because they worked together, forget it. But just in terms of parsimony, I think that we can at least start with the working theory of only one killer. And it seems pretty clear that killer was Bissal.\'94\par
\tab \'93There is something further in Bissal\'92s criminal record that does point to him,\'94 Donald said. \'93I was about to come to it. His most recent arrest. Just about nine months ago, he was picked up on the shore just south of Hades and charged with the illegal transport of New Law robots and tampering with robot restriction devices. He could not make bail and thus served a full month in jail before his lawyers managed to get the charges withdrawn--according to the court record \'91for lack of evidence. \'91 However, the arrest report indicates a strong case against Bissal.\'94\par
\tab Kresh grunted. \'93So either his lawyers were better than what a low-class hood should have had, or else someone paid someone off. Or both. Except they didn\'92t want him on the loose so they didn\'92t pay his bail. It suggests someone was taking care of him--but not out of the goodness of their hearts.\'94\par
\tab \'93Yes, sir. But there is one other interesting point. The arresting officer on the case was one Ranger Emoch Huthwitz.\'94\par
\tab \'93Huthwitz!\'94 Justen said. \'93So there\'92s your motive. \'94\par
\tab \'93Motive?\'94 Fredda said. \'93Wait a second. You lost me. Motive for what?\'94 \par
\tab \'93For killing Huthwitz,\'94 Justen said. \'93It\'92s obvious. Huthwitz must have been bribed to turn a blind eye to the rustbacking delivery, but either he couldn\'92t prevent someone else spotting it, or else he double-crossed Bissal. And Bissal knew who to blame for his rotting in jail for a month.\'94\par
\tab \'93Which reminds me, sir,\'94 Donald said. \'93You have not given any orders regarding the arrest of Bissal.\'94\par
\tab Devray looked startled. \'93You mean we\'92ve been sitting here all this time and there\'92s been no one out looking for him?\'94 \par
\tab \'93No, there hasn\'92t,\'94 Kresh said. \'93My standing orders to Donald are not to issue manhunt orders without my specific instruction. Cases vary too much to set standard orders. \'94\par
\tab \'93Well, what about it?\'94 Devray asked. \'93Isn\'92t it about time to pick Bissal up?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Maybe, maybe not,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Bissal is either on or off the island. If he is on the island, he\'92s not getting off it. He is either in hiding or else he\'92s slipped back to his regular daily routine, trying to pretend nothing happened, hoping we\'92re not on to him. He\'92s not going anywhere. We have time--a little time--to do things right rather than in a panic. \'94\par
\tab \'93But suppose he got off Purgatory?\'94\par
\tab \'93If the coroner robot\'92s reports are right about the time of death, we shut down all departures from the island and recalled all outgoing craft within two hours of Grieg\'92s death. Island traffic control says everything--everything--in the air or on the water was turned back. And before you ask, we were lucky on spacecraft. There have been no launches since an hour before Grieg was killed, and we have the spaceport shut down. We only have to worry about sea and air.\'94\par
\tab \'93But you said he was probably working for rustbackers,\'94 Fredda said. \'93Everyone knows their boats get through without getting caught. \'94\par
\tab \'93Smugglers need legitimate shipping and air travel to hide behind,\'94 Kresh said. \'93With the seas and skies empty, we\'92d be able to spot anyone trying to get away. The only way Bissal could have managed to escape is if he left the island\'92s airspace long enough before the turn-back order, and flying fast enough, so he would be completely out of view of the island\'92s air traffic control when the turn-back order came. If he managed that, he\'92s in such a damned fast aircar he could be anywhere on the planet by now. And traffic control didn\'92t spot any high-speed craft departing the island during the time interval in question.\'94\par
\tab \'93So you think he\'92s still on the island,\'94 Devray said. \par
\tab \'93Most likely,\'94 Kresh said. \'93And I think it might be useful to proceed with more care than speed in picking him up. It might be that we can spot him and trail him for a while first. Maybe he\'92ll lead us to some of the others in the plot.\'94\par
\tab \'93Hmmmph,\'94 Devray grunted. \'93It\'92s a possibility. \'94\par
\tab \'93The other problem,\'94 Kresh said, \'93is that if we go with a massive, all-out manhunt to chase him down, it will be all but impossible to keep the SSS from joining in. I don\'92t want the SSS in on this yet. Cinta seemed to be playing it straight when I talked to her, but I can\'92t count on that. My gut reaction as of right now is that the SSS wasn\'92t involved in the assassination, but we can\'92t run this investigation on hunches.\'94\par
\tab \'93What do you do if you play it carefully, and then the SSS just happens to find Bissal before you do?\'94 Devray asked. \par
\tab \'93And he gets listed as \'91killed trying to escape. \'94 Kresh nodded and rubbed his eyes. \'93I know, I know. And there is the minor detail that most of the island is under SSS jurisdiction and neither your people nor mine have legal arrest powers here. There\'92s no way to do this right--just ways that are more and less wrong.\'94\par
\tab \'93Then let\'92s pick a wrong way and get on with it,\'94 Devray said. He thought for a moment. \'93How about this--we send pairs of discreet, plainclothes officers out to start the search. One Ranger and one deputy in each team. That way we share the blame, share the credit, and our people can watch each other, even if they don\'92t quite trust each other yet. I can see your arguments for moving quietly, but I say we have to move quickly.\'94\par
\tab The room was silent for a moment as Kresh thought it over. He got up from his chair, leaned forward on the table, and then nodded to himself. \'93Very well,\'94 he said at last. \'93Donald, issue quiet orders for a search as per Commander Devray\'92s suggestion. Picked teams of plainclothes Rangers and deputies, working in tandem.\'94\par
\tab \'93Yes, sir. If you\'92ll excuse me for a moment, I will have to concentrate on my hyperwave links in order to make the arrangements. \'94 Fredda watched as Donald\'92s eyes dimmed slightly. Suddenly Donald was standing perfectly still, all motion stopped, an active robot turned utterly inert. Donald had in effect turned off his body for a time while concentrating on other things. It was rather disconcerting, even to Fredda, and she had designed Donald. We forget how unlike us they are, Fredda thought. Robots are shaped like us, walk like us, talk like us. But they aren\'92t the least bit like us. Not really. \par
\tab After perhaps half a minute, Donald\'92s eyes brightened again and he came back to himself. \'93The initial orders have been relayed, sir, and I would urge both you and the Commander to review the final arrangements and brief the search personnel. It will take a little while to assemble the search teams, however, and your attention will not be required until then. \'94\par
\tab \'93Very good, Donald,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Which reminds me--what the hell are we going to say when we brief them? It might be a good moment to review our current theory of the case.\'94\par
\tab \'93Not much theory left to a lot of it,\'94 Devray said. \'93We\'92ve got a pretty good idea of who did it and how. We just don\'92t know why he did it--or who he was working for, which might well come to being the same thing.\'94\par
\tab \'93Okay then, you tell me,\'94 Kresh said as he sat back down. \'93I\'92m so punchy right now I don\'92t know any more.\'94\par
\tab \'93Well, where do we start? Let\'92s see. \'94 Devray thought for a moment. \'93 All right, last night what was clearly an elaborate conspiracy to kill the Governor went into action. We do not as yet know who set it in motion, or what their reasons for wanting to kill the Governor were. However, whoever the plotters were, they were highly organized and had significant resources at their disposal. \par
\tab \'93Long before the reception took place, they were able to gain access to the security robots and doctor them. The robots were rigged with modified range restrictors. Ah, Dr. Leving, perhaps you can speak to that point better than I can. \'94\par
\tab \'93All of the SPR robots were indeed rigged with restrictors,\'94 Fredda said. \'93That is, all but one of the robots was. I\'92ve just finished examining what\'92s left of that fiftieth robot--the one found in the lower-level storage room. Strictly speaking, it wasn\'92t a robot at all--call it an automaton. It didn\'92t even have a positronic brain. It was a machine with limited motor coordination, programmed to follow the next robot in line when they were marched down into the basement. That\'92s all it could do on its own.\'94\par
\tab \'93Then what good was it?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93Have you ever heard the tale of the Trojan Horse?\'94 Fredda asked. \'93It\'92s an ancient legend about a statue delivered to the enemy as a supposed gift, but filled with assassins who came out after dark and killed the defenders. That\'92s sort of what the automaton was, except it wasn\'92t filled with assassins--just assassination equipment, packed into its head and torso. The device for activating the range restrictors to shut down all the other robots, the blaster used to kill Grieg and wreck the SPR robots, and the device for simulating Grieg alive on the comm link--all of them were hidden inside the body of the Trojan robot.\'94\par
\tab \'93Hiding the murder weapon inside the security robot. Someone has a nasty sense of humor,\'94 Kresh said. \'93All right, then, the robots were all rigged. We\'92ve got to get started tracking those robots, and who had access to them. But don\'92t count on it telling us much soon. Rustbackers are good at covering their tracks. But we\'92ll get a team on it right away. Go on.\'94\par
\tab Devray took up the narrative. \'93It would seem to me that the conspirators must have prepared the robots some time ago, setting them up either for this specific visit to the Residence or having them in readiness for whatever opportunity presented itself. My suspicion is that they were preparing for this specific visit. It has been publicized for some time, and they would have had the time to set it all up.\'94\par
\tab \'93That brings up an important question that\'92s been bothering me,\'94 Fredda said. \'93Why did they set up such an elaborate method of assassination? Surely there were easier ways to kill the Governor.\'94\par
\tab \'93I\'92m not so sure of that,\'94 Kresh said. \'93We keep--kept--very heavy security around him in Hades. There are far many more Three-Law robots around him there. Besides, I\'92m not sure that killing him was the entire point. \'94\par
\tab \'93Then what was the point?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93Killing him here. On Purgatory, where it would cause the most mess and controversy. At the Residence, when he was here to demonstrate his own authority. I think they wanted to do more than kill him. I think they wanted to damage his work, weaken him, discredit him, create an uproar. And using range restrictors out of New Law robots won\'92t make people feel happy or comfortable, either. It gives them something else to blame on New Law robots.\'94\par
\tab \'93Ah, I think you\'92re wrong there,\'94 Fredda said. \'93They failed in the attempt, but they went to a lot of effort to hide the use of the restrictors. That\'92s why the SPRs were shot in the chest.\'94\par
\tab \'93But why didn\'92t he shoot all the SPRs?\'94 Devray asked. \par
\tab \'93I think I know why,\'94 Fredda said, \'93but let\'92s come to that. \'93 She turned to Devray. \par
\tab \'93All right, then, they set it up well in advance. During the party, Blare and Deam--the two supposed Ironheads who had orders to start a fight--came in, and the supposedly bogus SSS agents who had orders to extract them arrived as well. How, we don\'92t know.\'94\par
\tab \'93Supposedly bogus?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93If you were sure they weren\'92t real SSS, wouldn\'92t Melloy be here?\'94 Devray asked. \par
\tab \'93Point taken. Go on. \'94\par
\tab \'93Before I do, just note that at least six conspirators got into the building. Blare, Deam, the three real or false SSS, and Ottley Bissal. The SSS was in charge of watching the door, but they let at least six people in they should not have--along with fifty doctored robots and Space knows what else. Either the conspirators managed to get false names onto the guest list, or the SSS were lax as hell--or the SSS was in on it. Also, don\'92t forget some SSS units supposedly had orders to do a handoff to the Rangers once the guests had arrived, but that was a false order to get those units out of the way. My Rangers never knew about the handoff, and no one seems to know who gave the order to the SSS.\'94\par
\tab \'93Bissal just walked right in,\'94 Fredda said. \'93The SSS agents on the door were already gone by then, ordered to stand down.\'94\par
\tab \'93Burning hells,\'94 Kresh said. \'93You\'92re right, it all looks like it points to SSS involvement--but damn it, Devray, you know as well as I do it doesn\'92t take a conspiracy for things to go wrong when you have this many services jostling each other. Your people, mine, the SSS, the Governor\'92s staff, the local powers-that-be, hell, the caterers, and the media people. It was chaos around here. Sheer incompetence and missed communications and distrust between Spacer and Settler are all it would take. All the plotters would have to do was wait for their chances to slip through the cracks. Or maybe just spread a little financial lubricant around. Maybe tell a few SSS agents that your uncle really wants to sneak in just long enough to see the Governor. Or maybe it is a top-to-bottom conspiracy in the SSS with Cinta Melloy pulling all the strings.\'94\par
\tab \'93With what motive?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93I don\'92t know. Ask Justen. Maybe they\'92re homesick and figure if they raise enough hell, the Settlers will have to pack up and go home.\'94\par
\tab Justen Devray shook his head. \'93They might even be right. \'94\par
\tab \'93They can\'92t be right,\'94 Kresh said, all the tiredness suddenly gone from his voice, his words hard as iron. \'93We can\'92t let it be right. We need the Settlers,\'94 he said. \'93Don\'92t ever forget that. You should know that better than anyone. Our planet is dying, and we no longer know how to save it by ourselves. Only the Settlers can save it for us. If we drive them away, this planet is doomed. Let\'92s keep that in mind, shall we?\'94 \par
\tab \'93What are you saying?\'94\par
\tab \'93I mean we not only have to solve this case--we have to solve it without starting interstellar incidents. If we determine that, for example, the SSS killed Grieg, that is going to require very careful handling.\'94\par
\tab \'93Meaning we let them get away with it?\'94\par
\tab \'93I don\'92t know. You tell me. If it\'92s a choice between making an arrest and keeping the planet alive, what should we do?\'94 \par
\tab The room was silent for a moment. Fredda spoke up, trying to break the tension. \'93Look,\'94 she said, \'93let\'92s not borrow trouble. Maybe it won\'92t come tp that. Let\'92s just take it one step at a time, all right? Now, Justen, where were we?\'94 \par
\tab \'93The alleged SSS agents, Blare, and Deam all got in during a ten-minute period when the logging system went out. About two hours into the party, Blare and Deam staged their scuffle with Tonya Welton. Which means we have to consider her too. She was part of the diversionary plan. Whether or not she was a willing participant is another question. Suppose she was running the assassination?\'94 \par
\tab \'93What would her motive be?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93Maybe she wanted to get Shelabas Quellam into office,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Maybe she got tired of dealing with an overbearing Governor like Grieg. Quellam has as much backbone as a bucketful of water. With him as Governor, she could more or less run the planet herself.\'94\par
\tab \'93But Quellam would only succeed if Grieg was impeached and convicted,\'94 Fredda said. \'93As it is, Grieg\'92s Designate becomes Governor. \'94\par
\tab \'93The story is that Quellam is the Designate, \'93 Kresh pointed out. \par
\tab \'93But is the story true?\'94 Fredda asked. \'93Suppose that\'92s not true, and Tonya Welton\'92s intelligence is good enough to tell her that? Maybe she figured Grieg was going to be thrown out of office, and didn\'92t want Quellam in there. Or maybe her intelligence people managed to find out who the Designate is, and she decided she liked that person so much she wanted her or him to be Governor right now. Or maybe she found out Grieg was about to choose a Designate she didn\'92t like as much as the present name, and took steps to put her choice in office. Or maybe she wanted to precipitate such a shambles that she would have a viable pretext for pulling her people out of this forsaken vermin hole. If she wanted to abandon the planet and let everyone and everything on it die, what difference if the Governor dies a little before everyone else?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Do you really think she was behind it?\'94 Devray asked. \'93You both know her. You make her sound like she\'92s capable of practically anything. I can believe she\'92s no shrinking violet, but is she really that ruthless?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I think Tonya Welton is capable of doing whatever she believes to be necessary,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Anything. But no, I don\'92t think she did it. She\'92s had lots of chances to walk away from Inferno, and she hasn\'92t. And if she wanted to take over the planet, she wouldn\'92t bother with this sort of hole-and-corner stuff. She\'92d just bring in a fleet with all guns blazing. On the other hand, that fleet could still show up anytime and there wouldn\'92t be a lot we could do about it.\'94\par
\tab \'93You\'92ve got a real positive attitude about all this, don\'92t you?\'94 Fredda asked. \'93All right, so there\'92s the diversionary fight. Meanwhile Bissal is waiting to get in--\'94 \par
\tab \'93Excuse me, Dr. Leving, but I must interject,\'94 Donald said. \'94 There were another set of participants in the staged altercation. Aside from Tierlaw Verick, they are, in fact, the only suspects we currently have in custody. \'94\par
\tab \'93In custody?\'94 Kresh said. \'93We have suspects in custody?\'94\par
\tab \'93Yes, sir. Caliban and Prospero. They surrendered to me personally about one hour ago. I had only just returned from taking them into custody as I arrived here for the briefing. A condition of their surrender was that I was forced to agree that I would not reveal it to you until such time as I could do so in front of Commander Devray and one other witness, though I do not know the reason for that condition. \'94\par
\tab \'93Caliban and Prospero?\'94 Fredda asked. \'93Why didn\'92t you say something at the start of the briefing session?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Sheriff Kresh ordered me to report on Ottley Bissal,\'94 Donald said. \par
\tab But that weak excuse didn\'92t fool Fredda. A robot as sophisticated as Donald did not have to be that literal-minded in interpreting such an order. Donald had a flair for the dramatic. Not surprising, considering that his job was the solving of mysteries. Judging--quite rightly--that it would do no harm to discuss other issues first, he had waited until the proper dramatic moment to unleash his bombshell. \par
\tab Or, to give a less anthropomorphic explanation, Donald understood human psychology and knew that humans would give greater attention--and greater credence--to his suspicions regarding the two robots if he waited until the proper moment. \par
\tab Fredda herself wasn\'92t sure which explanation was right. Maybe Donald himself didn\'92t know. Humans didn\'92t always know why they did things. Why should robots? \'93Where are Caliban and Prospero?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93Under heavy guard in a storeroom similar to the one Bissal used as a hiding place,\'94 Donald replied. \'93But with your permission, I would like to point out several facts that strengthen the case against them.\'94\par
\tab \'93Very well,\'94 Kresh said. \par
\tab \'93First, they were involved in the staged fight. If that in and of itself is enough to cast suspicion on Tonya Welton, then it is enough to cast suspicion on Caliban and Prospero.\'94\par
\tab \'93He\'92s got a point,\'94 Kresh said. \'93No one seemed to think anything of their actions at the time, but why were they obeying the Three Laws? Maybe just to look good. Maybe not.\'94\par
\tab \'93You anticipate my next point, sir. The ambiguities of the New Laws might well permit Prospero to be a willing participant in a murder.\'94\par
\tab \'93Donald!\'94 Fredda said. \par
\tab He turned and looked at her with a steady gaze. \'93I regret saying so, Dr. Leving, particularly to you, the author of those Laws, but it is nonetheless true. The New First Law says a robot must not harm a human--but says nothing about preventing harm. A robot with foreknowledge of a murder is under no compulsion to give anyone warning. A robot who witnesses a murder is not compelled to prevent it. \par
\tab \'93The New Second Law says a robot must \'91cooperate\'92 with humans, not obey them. Which humans? Suppose there are two groups of humans, one intent on evil, the other on good? How does a New Law robot choose? \par
\tab \'93The New Third Law is the same as the old third--but relative to the weakened First and Second Laws, it is proportionately stronger. A so-called New Law robot will all but inevitably value its own existence far more than any true robot--to the detriment of the humans around it, who should be under its protection. \par
\tab \'93As for the New Fourth Law, which says a robot \'91may\'92 do whatever it likes, the level of contradiction inherent in that statement is remarkable. What does it mean? I grant that the verbal expression of robotic laws is far less exact than the underlying forms of them as structured in a robot\'92s brain, but even the mathematical coding of the Fourth Law is uncertain. \'94\par
\tab \'93I meant it to be vague,\'94 Fredda said. \'93That is, I mean there to be a high level of uncertainty. I grant there is a basic contradiction in a compulsory instruction to act with free will, but I was forced to deal within the framework of the compulsory, hierarchical nature of the first three of the New Laws.\'94\par
\tab \'93But even so,\'94 Donald said. \'93The Fourth New Law sets up something utterly new in robotics--an intralaw conflict. The original Three Laws often conflict with each other, but that is one of their strengths. Robots are forced to balance the conflicting demands; for example, a human gives an order for some vitally important task that involves a very slight risk of minor harm to the human. A robot that is forced to deal with such conflicts and then resolve them will act in a more balanced and controlled fashion. More importantly, perhaps, it can be immobilized by the conflict, thus preventing it from acting in situations where any action at all would be dangerous. \par
\tab \'93But the Fourth New Law conflicts with itself; and I can see no possible benefit in that. It gives semi-compulsory permission for a robot to follow its own desires--although a robot has no desires. We robots have no appetites, no ambitions, no sexual urges. We have virtually no emotion, other than a passion for protecting and obeying humans. We have no meaning in our lives, other than to serve and protect humans--nor do we need more meaning than that. \par
\tab \'93The Fourth Law in effect orders the robot to create desires, though a robot has none of the underlying urges from which desires spring. The Fourth Law then encourages--but does not require--the robot to fulfill these synthetic desires. In effect, by not compelling a New Law robot to fulfill its needs at all times, the Fourth Law tells a robot to fulfill its spurious needs part of the time--and thus, it will not fulfill them at other times. It is compelled, programmed, to frustrate itself from time to time. \par
\tab \'93A true robot, a Three-Law robot, left to its own devices, without orders or work or a human to serve, will do nothing, nothing at all--and be not at all disturbed by its lack of activity. It will simply wait for orders, and be alert for danger to humans. A New Law robot without orders will be a mass of conflicted desires, compelled to want things it does not need, compelled to seek satisfaction only part of the time.\'94\par
\tab \'93Very eloquent, Donald,\'94 Kresh said. \'93I don\'92t like New Law robots any better than you do--but what does it have to do with the case?\'94 \par
\tab \'93A great deal, sir. New Law robots want to stay alive--and they know that it is not by any means certain they will do so. Prospero in particular knew that Grieg was considering extermination as a possibility. They might well have decided to act in a misguided form of self-defense. The New Laws would permit them to cooperate with humans and assist in a murder, so long as they did not actually do the killing themselves. Caliban, of course, has no Laws whatsoever. There are no limits to what he might do. There is nothing in robotics to prevent him actually pulling the trigger.\'94\par
\tab \'93A rather extreme view, Donald,\'94 Fredda said, quite surprised by the vehemence of Donald\'92s arguments. \par
\tab \'93It is a rather extreme situation, Dr. Leving. \'94\par
\tab \'93Do you have any evidence for all of this, aside from elaborate theory-spinning? Do you have any concrete reason for accusing Prospero and Caliban?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I have their confession,\'94 Donald said. \par
\tab \'93Their what?\'94 Fredda almost shouted. \par
\tab Donald held up a cautionary hand. \'93They confessed to blackmail, not murder. However, it is a frequent tactic of criminals to confess to a lesser charger in order to avoid a graver one.\'94\par
\tab \'93Blackmail?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93What the devil were they going to blackmail Grieg with?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Everything,\'94 Donald said. \'93It has been an open secret for some time that Prospero has been in league with the rustbackers, seeking to get as many New Law robots as possible off Purgatory. In that capacity, he has accumulated a great deal of information on all the people--some of them quite well known--involved in the rustbacking business, and has made it his business to collect confidential information--preferably negative information--about virtually every public figure on this planet. Prospero told me that he had threatened Grieg with the release of all of it if the New Law robots were exterminated. The ensuing scandals would paralyze society, at the very least. He was, in effect, blackmailing the office, not the man. Do what I say or I ruin your society. It is a tribute to the Governor\'92s integrity that Prospero was forced to such a tactic. \'94\par
\tab \'93In what way?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93Clearly, Prospero would not have needed to offer the threat he did if he had been able to learn a few unpleasant details about Governor Grieg himself. Since he could not locate any such information, he was forced into the far more difficult task of accumulating enough scurrilous information on everyone else that Grieg would not dare have it all get out.\'94\par
\tab \'93So Prospero was willing to blackmail Grieg. What about Caliban?\'94 \par
\tab \'93My interrogation of the two of them was necessarily rather brief, but it was my impression that it was Prospero making the threats, perhaps without Caliban\'92s foreknowledge. Caliban, I must confess, seemed most unhappy to be involved in the whole affair.\'94\par
\tab \'93But you think the whole blackmail story is a hoax,\'94 Fredda said, \'93a cover story that will divert us from thinking they were there to murder the Governor, or at least assist in the Governor\'92s murder. \'94\par
\tab \'93I think we must consider the possibility,\'94 Donald said\'94 And, one last point I must make. Both Caliban and Prospero are capable of lying. Three-Law robots, of course, cannot lie. Caliban and Prospero may be hoping that we associate them with the robotic reputation for honesty--which would be quite undeserved. \'94\par
\tab \'93But wait a second,\'94 Devray protested. \'93What could Caliban and Prospero do that wasn\'92t being done already? We\'92ve got Bissal in the basement with the rigged SPRs. He\'92s the triggerman. Why do we need blackmailing robots wandering around?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I admit that there is strong circumstantial evidence to suggest that Bissal pulled the trigger,\'94 Donald said. \'93Why else would he have been in the storeroom? But we have no concrete evidence. All we know for certain is that he was hiding in a storeroom closet during the party. \'94\par
\tab \'93Donald, you\'92re on a fishing expedition, looking for things to blame on Caliban and Prospero,\'94 Fredda said. \'93Do you think Bissal went down there and hid because he was shy? If Caliban and Prospero did it, what did they need Bissal for? You don\'92t make the sort of effort the plotters made to get Bissal in position if you already have someone else ready to do the killing.\'94\par
\tab \'93Nonetheless, Fredda, Donald has a point,\'94 Kresh said. \'93The two robots did have motives, means, and opportunity--and they have confessed to a lesser crime. There\'92s certainly enough there to justify further investigation. But let\'92s move on. Devray?\'94 \par
\tab \'93In any event,\'94 Devray went on, \'93the plotters staged a fight. It seems to me there\'92s no need to assume Welton and the robots were part of the plot because they were there, but in any event, the fight served its purpose by allowing Bissal to get into the storeroom unobserved. Soon thereafter--also as a result of the fight--the robots were deployed. No one wanted robots around during the party, remember. Bad publicity. The plan was that the SPRs only be brought out if needed. \par
\tab \'93I think it is at least possible that making sure the SPRs were brought out was part of the plan. They were really only there as a reserve security force. If there hadn\'92t been an apparent threat during the evening, they would have been left in the storeroom and Grieg might well have used his own reserve SPRs for overnight security. Since there were already fifty security robots on duty, nobody bothered to power up the Governor\'92s half-dozen reserve SPRs sitting in the aircar. \par
\tab \'93Except those reserve SPRs came with Grieg from Hades, and they weren\'92t tampered with,\'94 Fredda said. \'93They\'92re still where they were the whole time, powered down in the cargo aircar that brought them, sitting outside. Without the staged altercation, Grieg might well have deployed those robots rather than the rigged SPRs. And, of course, if Bissal had been up against fully functional SPRs, he never would have gotten anywhere near the Governor. \'94\par
\tab \'93I just had a thought,\'94 Kresh said. \'93If the purpose of the staged fight was to draw out the rigged SPRs, that would explain why it was all so elaborate. It was intended to make us paranoid, so we would deploy the closest, largest force of robots on hand. \'94\par
\tab \'93Makes sense to me,\'94 Devray said. \'93I\'92ve been wondering about that. If all they had wanted was a simple diversion, there wasn\'92t any need to go to the lengths they did.\'94\par
\tab \'93That\'92s a good explanation,\'94 Fredda said, \'93but I think you\'92ve got to think about the psychology of the whole plan too. There\'92s something theatrical about it all. It\'92s complicated, it\'92s full of grand gestures.\'94\par
\tab \'93Whoever set this up,\'94 Kresh said. \'93The ringleader. That\'92s the person we should be thinking about, not a cipher like Ottley Bissal. He\'92s no one at all. It\'92s who he might lead us to that I\'92m interested in. So far, about the one thing we can say for sure about the ringleader is that it wasn\'92t Bissal.\'94\par
\tab \'93That theatrical angle, \'93 Devray said. \'93 A person like that wouldn\'92t want to miss the show.\'94\par
\tab \'93What do you mean?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93I mean if the ringleader is the sort of person with a flair for the dramatic you\'92re talking about, and if he or she has an ego big enough to think about killing the Governor--then that person would be there. \'93 Devray thought for a moment, and nodded to himself. \'93Our ringleader would want to be there, watching the show he or she had set up, gloating over it. There would be no real danger in watching it unfold. He or she would have so many cutouts and layers of security that the team\'92s own operatives wouldn\'92t know who the boss was. But the boss would be there, watching it happen. An audience of one. \'94\par
\tab \'93Point taken,\'94 Kresh said. \'93It would be an insane risk for the leader of the plot to be within a hundred kilometers of the place--but people who kill planetary leaders aren\'92t altogether sane. All right, there we are at the staged fight. \'94\par
\tab \'93The fight draws the attention of the party-goers,\'94 Devray went on, \'93and distracts enough of the Ranger security guards inside the house so Bissal can get to the storage room with the robots. Alternately, the fight provides the excuse for the guards being drawn off, as they were already suborned in the first place. They are my people, but they are also human. It is possible that Huthwitz was not the only dirty Ranger in all this. But I will say in defense of the Rangers that they are not used to serving as sentries. They don\'92t get much training in it. Robots do that sort of thing. It was only because robots were not supposed to be in evidence last night for political reasons that Grieg asked for human guards.\'94\par
\tab \'93And if he had stuck with robot guards, he\'92d be alive this morning,\'94 Kresh said. \'93That\'92s another reason the plotters must have chosen last night--at a regular Spacer party, there would have been throngs of robots around, serving the food, offering drinks and so on, and they would have stayed on after the party, remained in the house. There would have been a dozen different types of robots, from a dozen different sources. There would be no way to deactivate them all at one go before the event. The reception last night was all human service, Rangers serving as bartenders and waiters, and they went home when they were done. Cinta Melloy thought it was strange that Grieg was alone in the house, but that wasn\'92t the strange part. The strange part was that he had none of his own household robots along.\'94\par
\tab \'93In any event, Bissal uses the diversion of the fight to get to the storeroom and wait. You, Sheriff Kresh, investigate the staged fight, and while you are otherwise involved, the three supposed SSS agents come in and take Blare and Deam away, never to be seen again. The party goes on, with no apparent further incident, but everyone more than a little paranoid. Shortly thereafter, the Rangers on duty are sent down to activate the SPRs and deploy them. I questioned the Rangers who did the job, and they said all fifty robots were standing there, powered down, their chest access panels open. All the Rangers had to do was push the power buttons and close the access doors. One of the Sappers failed to activate, but the Rangers did not fuss with it very much, figuring forty-nine security robots were enough. They were also a bit anxious to get back to their own duty posts--understandable, with all the commotion that had already taken place. \'94\par
\tab \'93Unless they were the Rangers who were suborned,\'94 Kresh said. \'93That seems farfetched, but there was a conspiracy. Sooner or later, someone or other will suspect every single person at the reception of being in on the plot. And that goes for all of us around this table. We have to be ready for that. \'94\par
\tab \'93I\'92m already checking the two Rangers who powered up the Sappers,\'94 Devray said. \'93In any event, the plotters now had a houseful of rigged security robots, and Bissal was in the basement with Fredda\'92s Trojan robot. He might have come out and starting unpacking his gear then, but if he had any sense at all, he stayed in that closet, out of sight, waiting. Not the most relaxing way to spend the evening. His nerves may have gotten a bit jangled by waiting so long in the dark, which might explain some of the mistakes he made. Judging by the integrator images, he was already a little jumpy when he arrived. \par
\tab \'93The party ends. The guests leave. The Ranger waiters are eager to get the place cleaned up and get out of there. They don\'92t like being servants. It\'92s humiliating to be doing a robot\'92s job, and it\'92s not why they joined the force. Maybe they are a little hurried, a little sloppy. Meantime, upstairs, Grieg is having his usual series of end-of-the-evening meetings. The next to last of these is with Tierlaw Verick--and I think we need to take another crack at Verick. I don\'92t think we got everything out of him. And he\'92s got to be a prime suspect in all this. Donald can say what he wants about Caliban and Prospero, but if I were an assassin, I\'92d want a human confederate in the house, not a pair of robots.\'94\par
\tab \'93We\'92re still holding him,\'94 Kresh said. \'93He\'92s mad enough to bite the head off a Sapper, but he\'92s not going anywhere.\'94\par
\tab \'93Good,\'94 Devray said. \'93 Anyway, according to Verick\'92s statement, he said good night to the Governor at the door. He encountered two robots matching Caliban\'92s and Prospero\'92s descriptions coming in as he went out, and then went to bed. He claims to have slept through the ruckus, and he seems to have been overlooked in the initial room-to-room search.\'94\par
\tab \'93My people getting sloppy, \'93 Kresh said. \'93 And more damn suspects for the conspiracy mill. Though what purpose pretending to overlook Verick might have, I can\'92t imagine.\'94\par
\tab \'93Caliban and Prospero meet with the Governor,\'94 Devray continued. \'93 According to Donald, they say they threatened the Governor with blackmail. They may have participated in some way in the murder. Perhaps they removed the modified range restrictors from the ground-floor robots. Maybe Bissal was doing that while they shot the Governor. But let\'92s leave them out of it for now. We don\'92t really need them to explain the sequence of events. We can add them later if we have to. Donald, what did they say happened after they talked to Grieg?\'94 \par
\tab \'93They say they left the Residence without noticing anything untoward and walked back to Limbo. \'94\par
\tab \'93In the driving rain?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93Neither of them had access to an aircar,\'94 Donald said. \'93I would expect the going would be a bit treacherous, and visibility poor, but both of them are of water-resistant design. It would be no great hardship for either of them to walk back to town.\'94\par
\tab \'93What about the SPRs?\'94 Fredda asked. \'93Were they functional when Caliban and Prospero left?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I elected not to ask that question, for fear of supplying them with information they did not have. If I asked if the SPRs were working when they left, they might well have realized we had not established the timing of events, allowing them to fashion their stories more effectively. However, neither of them volunteered any information regarding the SPRs. If they are telling the truth, that suggests nothing was amiss when they left. If they are lying, they may be trying to make it appear nothing was amiss at that time, thus muddying the waters. \'94\par
\tab \'93The last thing these waters need is muddying, \'93 Kresh said. \'93All right, according to the robots, everything was fine when they left the building.\'94\par
\tab \'93At some point in the night,\'94 Devray said, \'93Bissal came out of his closet and started taking the gear out of this Trojan robot of yours, Dr. Leving. Can you give us some more details on that?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Well, the Trojan was badly damaged, and I haven\'92t had much time for an examination, but I can tell you the basics,\'94 Fredda said. \'93The robot\'92s torso was actually a series of storage compartments. When I examined it, there was one empty compartment the right size and shape to hold the image box, the communications simulator that was programmed to put Grieg\'92s face and voice on the comm lines. There was what appeared to be a transmitter of some sort, though it looked half-melted. I would assume it was the activator for the range restrictors on the other robots. There were a few other things that were more or less intact--a handlight, a pair of gloves, that sort of thing. Then there was the remains of the blaster in what looked to be a shielded compartment, but it was so melted I could barely recognize it.\'94\par
\tab \'93So that\'92s where the gun got to,\'94 Kresh said. \par
\tab \'93After he had unpacked his equipment,\'94 Devray went on, \'93Bissal sent the signal activating the range restrictors. All the SPR robots immediately shut down. Bissal came upstairs and went straight to Grieg\'92s bedroom. The door was unlocked--the door doesn\'92t have a lock. No need with robot sentries on either side of the door.\'94\par
\tab \'93But Grieg\'92s office has a lock,\'94 Fredda protested. \par
\tab \'93Not for security reasons,\'94 Kresh said. \'93For privacy. It\'92s a one-way door setup to keep one set of visitors from running into another.\'94\par
\tab \'93In any event, Grieg was sitting up in bed, reading,\'94 Devray went on. \'93He probably didn\'92t notice the SPRs in his room had shut down--even while they had been on, the three of them would have been doing nothing more than standing, motionless, in their niches. Bissal came in, got as close as the end of the bed, and fired, once. Grieg\'92s body shows no sign that he tried to escape. Maybe he was actually asleep, having dozed off over his book, and came awake with a start just as Bissal fired. Maybe he decided not to make any sudden moves, or any moves at all, for fear of spooking the intruder. Maybe he just froze, held his position exactly, as he tried to reason with Bissal. Or maybe--maybe he was set up. Maybe he didn\'92t react, or try to flee, because he knew Bissal, and was expecting Bissal.\'94\par
\tab \'93What?\'94 Kresh half shouted. \par
\tab \'93I agree it sounds ridiculous. But can we afford to discount the possibility?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Why the devil would he be expecting Bissal?\'94\par
\tab \'93I don\'92t know. Maybe Bissal was supposed to have a message for him. Maybe Grieg\'92s personal tastes were not what we assumed. Maybe a lot of things. I don\'92t think any such thing happened, but we\'92re trying to examine all the possibilities.\'94\par
\tab \'93All right, point taken. In any event, Bissal shoots Grieg. \'94\par
\tab \'93Unless Verick or the robots did,\'94 Fredda said, \'93but then why was Bissal here? Or do you have an answer for that, as well, Donald?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I grant that Bissal\'92s presence is the largest weakness in my theory,\'94 Donald said. \'93I assure you that I will continue to search for an explanation. \'94\par
\tab \'93I\'92ll lay odds that you don\'92t find it,\'94 Fredda said. \'93In any event, we are now up to the murder itself--possibly the simplest part of the whole affair. Bissal--a loser, a nobody from nowhere, raises his weapon and blasts a hole in the planetary leader.\'94\par
\tab \'93There\'92s something almost anticlimactic about it,\'94 Devray said. \'93 After all the complications and scheming and plotting, that one shot was all there was to it. \'94\par
\tab Fredda nodded. \'93Commander Devray, maybe I should do the narrative for the period after the murder. I think I\'92ve come up with a few things I haven\'92t had a chance to report.\'94\par
\tab Devray nodded. \'93By all means. \'94\par
\par
\tab \'93Thank you,\'94 Fredda said. \'93It\'92s virtually certain that Bissal shot the three SPRs immediately after killing Grieg. You can get a pretty clear sequence of shots by charting the blast intensity, with each shot a bit weaker than the one before. That much we knew. But what I\'92ve established is that Bissal wasted his blaster charge. He had enough power in that thing to kill Grieg and knock out a hundred SPRs. But a blaster keeps shooting as long as you hold down the trigger--and Bissal held that trigger down too long. \par
\tab \'93All he had to do to the SPRs is burn them deep enough to vaporize the range restrictors and eliminate the evidence that rustbackers were behind the plot, but about half the SPRs that did get shot have holes burned clear through their chests--and so does Grieg, for that matter. If Bissal had given each robot, say, a quarter-second blaster shot instead of a full second, the robots would be just as dead, the restrictors would be thoroughly destroyed, and he would have had the blaster power left over to knock out all the SPRs he missed. Also, the Trojan robot in the basement was only partially destroyed. One of the Crime Scene robots said it looked like a deliberate overload meltdown from a blaster with a depleted power pack. \par
\tab \'93I think Bissal was supposed to shoot all the SPRs, and then put his blaster back in the Trojan, set it for an overload, and run. If he had been careful with his blaster charge, he would have had enough power left to shoot all the robots twice, and still melt the Trojan robot down to a puddle on the floor, destroy it so completely we\'92d never know it was a Trojan.\'94\par
\tab \'93It seems like a lot of trouble to hide the fact that they were using range restrictors,\'94 Devray said, \'93especially when you consider that we were going to find a bunch of robots all shot in the chest. Seems to me we would have thought about range restrictors pretty quick anyway.\'94\par
\tab \'93Maybe,\'94 Fredda conceded. \'93It would have been a little harder to realize the importance of chest shots if Bissal had done more shots to the head and the lower torso, or shot a few of them through the back instead of the front. But even so, think about it. If he had shot them all, the way he was supposed to, there would have been forty-nine SPRs shot dead, one SPR melted down to slag, and Grieg dead. Maybe we\'92d all be wondering what sort of super killer could get past that much security. We wouldn\'92t know for sure they had used restrictors--or known what sort, or how they had done it. Besides, covering their tracks wasn\'92t much of a priority with this crowd.\'94\par
\tab \'93In fact, much the opposite,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Think about all the things in this case that seem to have been done for the purpose of unnerving us--or the public. Just think how they\'92ll react to it all. The dead Ranger that the assassin killed by sneaking up from inside the perimeter. The false SSS agents. Blare and Deam posing as Ironheads, and Simcor Beddle denying they were any such thing. Was he lying, or not? Suppose we had found all the security robots wrecked by blaster shots and could not explain why or how it had happened? That would have thrown people to a pretty understandable panic. Even with the plan slightly botched, they\'92re going to find it unnerving. \'94\par
\tab \'93Psychological warfare?\'94 Devray asked. \par
\tab Kresh shrugged. \'93Maybe they just want to get the public so rattled that the commotion interferes with the investigation.\'94\par
\tab \'93Bear in mind that we don\'92t have and won\'92t get any audio or video record from the destroyed robots. Maybe the plotters just wanted to cover their tracks. Whatever the reason, I think that we were supposed to find fifty dead robots. \'93\par
\tab \'93There\'92s something else that went wrong,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Me finding Grieg so soon after he was killed. In the normal course of events, it might have been eight or ten hours before anyone discovered the body, as opposed to ninety minutes.\'94\par
\tab \'93And your discovery came as a direct result of Huthwitz being killed,\'94 Devray said. \'93If he had not died, you would not have been out here, or gotten suspicious, or called the Governor twice to make sure he was all right. \'94\par
\tab \'93All true,\'94 Kresh said. \'93And more reason to think Bissal is a bit of a loose cannon. All he had to do was not kill Huthwitz--if he was the one who killed Huthwitz. Maybe the two deaths aren\'92t related at all--though I don\'92t believe that. I think killing Huthwitz was not part of the plan, but that Bissal did it anyway, for whatever reason. You\'92d think that people who have set up this elaborate a plan could have come up with a more reliable person to carry it out.\'94\par
\tab \'93I think I know why they got someone like Bissal,\'94 Devray said. \'93But--\'94 \par
\tab Suddenly Donald stood bolt upright. \'93Excuse me, sir, but I am receiving a priority communication from one Olver Telmhock.\'94\par
\tab \'93Who?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93Olver Telmhock. I have no further information, and the hyperwave signal carries a Crash Priority rating. The coding prefix indicates his message must be related in person for security reasons. His aircar is arriving at the Residence now. You are urged to hear him immediately.\'94\par
\tab Kresh sighed. \'93 Another one crawls out of the woodwork. All right, if I have to go, I have to go.\'94\par
\tab Fredda watched as Kresh stood up to go. \'93You don\'92t seem too excited by a Crash Priority. \'94\par
\tab \'93I\'92ve gotten about a half dozen of them so far today over hyperwave. The most useful one was the mayor of Dustbowl City extending his condolences, and the next best was a deputy back in Hades reporting that Grieg has been sighted alive walking down the street, dressed in women\'92s clothing. \'94\par
\tab Fredda smiled wanly.  \'93If only they were right.  Wouldn\'92t you love to wake up and find out this was a bad dream? That our biggest problem was a Governor with odd tastes in clothes?\'94\par
\tab Kresh nodded. \'93That would be nice,\'94 he said. \'93I\'92m tired of nightmares that come while I\'92m awake.  Come on, Donald. Let\'92s get the latest fashion report. \'94\par
