KRESH STEPPED INTO the interrogation room. Donald came in behind him, closed the door, and then took up a position next to and slightly behind Kresh, rather than retreating to a wall niche. Donald only stayed that close when he had some intimation that Kresh might be in some sort of danger. Kresh couldn\'92t see any particular peril in the current situation, but Kresh had learned some time ago to trust Donald\'92s reactions, even above his own. There was something here that Donald did not like; something he thought might be of some sort of possible danger. \par
\tab If so, then Donald was seeing things Kresh could not. All Kresh could see was a thin, reedy sort of man, Telmhock presumably, accompanied by a rather battered-looking robot. \par
\tab Telmhock was sitting at the table, facing the door, some papers spread out before him. He did not seem to be the sort of person who could endanger much of anyone. \par
\tab He was of indeterminate middle age, and his face was long and narrow, with a beaklike nose that might have given him a quite authoritative air, were it not for the distracted, almost dreamy, look in his blue-grey eyes. His clothes were at least twenty years out of fashion, and there was something a bit musty about them. His hair was a little on the longish side, though, if Kresh were any judge, not by choice. He had made no conscious decision on his hairstyle; rather he had merely forgotten to have it cut. There were even traces of dandruff on the shoulders of his jacket--a truly scandalous failing in Inferno\'92s overly fastidious society. \par
\tab His robot, which was of near-antique vintage, stood behind him. The robot was a dark grey in color, though it looked as if it had once been a gleaming jet-black. It was holding the handle of a briefcase no less battered than itself, and something about its rather assertive posture suggested that it was not likely to treat its master with the sort of craven slavishness of most Inferno robots. \par
\tab In short, the man looked like what he clearly was: an old-fashioned civil servant who took his work very seriously indeed, with his personal robot of many years service in attendance. \par
\tab \'93Sheriff Kresh?\'94 the man asked. \par
\tab \'93Yes. \'94 Who the devil else did he think it might be? \par
\tab \'93Hmm. Ha. Good. I am Professor Giver Telmhock. I am the dean of the law department of Hades University.\'94\par
\tab A very grand-sounding title, but it didn\'92t impress Kresh much. The university was not large, and the law department was small, even in proportion. There was not much call for lawyers on Inferno, praise be. \par
\tab Telmhock seemed to see that Kresh was underimpressed, and therefore added a few other titles to the mix. \'93I am, ah, also an adviser to the Attorney General, and to the late Governor on any number of legal matters. \'94\par
\tab \'93I see,\'94 Kresh said, though he did not. Nor was he impressed by the man\'92s resume. Not on Inferno. The population was small, and the duties of government and academic service light, with the result that there was a certain comic-opera flavor to the upper crust of society, with everyone seeming to claim a half-dozen offices, with all sorts of fancy titles that came complete with uniforms and badges and medallions that could be worn to parties. The staff robots did all the work while the office holders went to receptions. \par
\tab Kresh had been getting all sorts of calls from any number of just such nonofficials, offering help they could not provide and giving advice that would have been suicidal if taken. Telmhock was just about the lowest-ranking official to contact him--and the only one to come in person. \par
\tab Why the devil should he give half a damn about an \'93adviser\'94 to the Attorney General when the A. G. hadn\'92t set foot in her own office in the last year? Alvar Kresh stood over the prim little man, not trying very hard to conceal his annoyance and impatience. \'93Now then, Professor Telmhock, as you will appreciate, this is a rather busy time for me. \'94\par
\tab \'93Yes, I rather imagine it is,\'94 Telmhock replied, plainly not in any hurry at all to get to the point. \'93This is a shocking development. Absolutely shocking. \'94 He sat there, shaking his head mournfully. \par
\tab It seemed to Kresh as if the old boy was not prepared to say anything more without prompting. \'93I quite agree,\'94 he said. \'93However, Professor, I am quite pressed for time. You called me away from a rather urgent case review. I appreciate the condolence call, but I really must--\'94 \par
\tab \'93Condolence call?\'94 Telmhock asked. \'93I am not making a mere condolence call. Did I leave that impression? I certainly did not intend to do so. I would not wish to interrupt you needlessly.\'94\par
\tab Again, the man didn\'92t seem prepared to volunteer any actual information. Kresh forced himself to be calm. \'93 All right, then,\'94 he said, \'93perhaps you could tell me why you did feel the need to interrupt me. \'94 Not the most tactful of phrasings, but there were times when rudeness got things moving. \par
\tab \'93Oh, but of course,\'94 Telmhock said. \'93I think you will agree that it is a matter of some importance. I thought it might be wise if I talked to you about the succession to the late Governor\'92s office.\'94\par
\tab \'93I thought Shelabas Quellam was the Designate.\'94\par
\tab Telmhock looked at him oddly, and seemed to choose his words carefully. \'93 And so he was--up until a few days ago. \'94\par
\tab Suddenly Kresh was all attention. A change in the Designation? That could turn the case upside-down. \'93You\'92re quite right, Professor Telmhock. Information regarding the succession would be most useful, and of the greatest interest to me. \'93 Both the new Designate and the old would have motives for killing Grieg. The new Designate might have killed to seize power--while the old one, Shelabas, might have struck in desperation, in hopes of succeeding before the new Designation could be made official. \par
\tab Yes, of course. Why hadn\'92t he looked harder in that direction, toward Shelabas? Gain was always a likely motive for murder, and who could gain more than the Governor\'92s successor? If the assassination was a power grab, who was it who ended up gaining power? \par
\tab In plain terms, the new Governor would have to be a suspect in the case. Gain--and power--were first-rate motives. \'93But how do you come to have any knowledge of--ah--this subject?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I am the executor of the late Governor\'92s last will and testament,\'94 Telmhock said, a bit taken aback. \'93But you were not aware of that? Hmmm. Hah. Yes. \'94 The little man seemed to consider that piece of information carefully. \'93In light of the fact that you did not know who I was, or that I am executor to his will, I wonder--were you--are you--at least aware of the Governor\'92s new choice as Designate?\'94 \par
\tab \'93No,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Of course not. Why would he tell me?\'94 Confound the man! Couldn\'92t he get to the point? \par
\tab \'93Why indeed?\'94 Telmhock asked, looking toward his robot. \par
\tab \'93He did not know. I see. I see. \'94 He thought that bit of information over as well. \'93That does make things rather more interesting, doesn\'92t it, Stanmore?\'94 he asked, addressing his robot, before returning to his former air of distraction. \par
\tab \'93Yes, sir, it does,\'94 the robot replied, and then said no more. The robot Stanmore seemed to share its master\'92s reluctance to offer up any actual information. \par
\tab The four of them--Kresh, Donald, Telmhock, and Stanmore--remained in silence for perhaps half a minute before Kresh spoke again, struggling to keep his temper under control. \'93Professor Telmhock. I am currently running the most important investigation any law enforcement official has ever faced on this planet. The situation is extremely delicate and requires my full attention. I do not have the time to watch you meditate on my ignorance of the Governor\'92s will, or to watch you and your robot exchange pleasantries. If you know who the Governor-Designate is, or have any information that might be useful to me, tell it to me right now, as clearly and briefly as possible. Otherwise, I am going to arrest you for obstructing an official investigation. Is that clear?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Oh, dear!\'94 Telmhock all but squeaked. \'93Yes! My apologies,\'94 the little man said, clearly very startled. \par
\tab \'93Good,\'94 said Kresh. \'93Now then--who is the Designate?\'94\par
\tab \'93You. You are,\'94 Telmhock said, still rather flustered. \par
\tab There was a moment\'92s dead silence as Kresh tried to absorb what he had just heard. \'93I beg your pardon?\'94 he asked. \par
\tab \'93You are,\'94 Telmhock said. \'93You are the Governor-Designate.\'94\par
\tab \'93I don\'92t understand,\'94 Kresh said, his knees suddenly a bit weak. Me? The Designate? Why the devil would Grieg pick me? \par
\tab \'93It\'92s quite simple,\'94 Telmhock said. \'93The Governor changed his will just ten days ago. You are the Designate.\'94\par
\tab \'93Excuse me, Professor, but you have misstated the case,\'94 said Telmhock\'92s robot. \'93Alvar Kresh is not the Designate. \'94\par
\tab \'93Hmmm? Oh, yes, my. You\'92re quite right, Stanmore. I hadn\'92t considered the case fully enough. Quite right.\'94\par
\tab Kresh looked to the robot with a feeling of indescribable relief. Telmhock, addled old bureaucrat that he was, had gotten it wrong. \'93What is it he\'92s gotten wrong?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93If I\'92m not the Designate, who is?\'94 \par
\tab \'93No one is,\'94 said Stanmore. \'93You ceased being the Designate at the moment of Grieg\'92s death.\'94\par
\tab \'93Excuse me?\'94 Kresh said. \par
\tab \'93You were the Governor-Designate. But according to Infernal law, at the moment of Chanto Grieg\'92s death, you automatically succeeded to his office.\'94\par
\tab \'93The letter, Stanmore,\'94 said Telmhock. \par
\tab The robot extracted an envelope from his briefcase and handed it to Kresh, who accepted it quite mechanically. \'93I deliver this letter to you from Chanto Grieg on the occasion of his death, as per the instructions of the deceased. \'94\par
\tab \'93But I don\'92t know how to... \'94 Kresh\'92s voice trailed off. He was too numb with shock to say more. \par
\tab Olver Telmhock stood and offered a nervous smile as he stuck out his hand. \'93Congratulations--Governor Kresh. \'94\par
