\tab Tierlaw Verick sat in the comfortable chair of his comfortable room and raged silently against his imprisonment. \par
\tab No matter that the bed was soft, that the carpet was freshly vacuumed, that the closet was full of handsome clothes that could fit him--or nearly anyone else--in a pinch, that the refresher had every sort of soap and powder and potion. No matter that this room was as comfortable as the one he had slept in the night before, here at the Residence--that this room was virtually identical to it. He was a prisoner. He could not leave. He could stand up from his chair and try the door, even open it--but there would be a robotic sentry on the other side of it. He could look out the window onto the spacious grounds of the Residence--but he would see another vigilant robot there, as well. \par
\tab Robots! Literally surrounded by robots. Perhaps that was no more than a fitting punishment for his getting involved in the financial side of rustbacking. He should never have gotten involved with that miserable trade. It was no business for a Settler to be involved in. But the profits had been so huge, and he had been able to keep far away from the dirty side of the business. \par
\tab Much good his profits would do him now. Here he was, locked away, cut off, and no one would tell him anything. He had been given no reason at all for his being held. \par
\tab The door came open, and Verick was delighted to see the guard--the human guard, Pyman, his name was--coming in with Verick\'92s meal tray. \par
\tab Pathetic that he was so starved for company that the mere sight of a human being thrilled him so much. But Verick had always needed attention, an audience, someone to talk to, and he had been cultivating Pyman most assiduously. Pyman was, after all, Verick\'92s only link to the outside world, his only source of information. \par
\tab No doubt they were sending a human with his tray instead of a robot in the hope that Verick would be more likely to talk to a human, let something slip. Well, two could play that game. Pyman was far more likely than the average robot to say more than he should. \par
\tab Verick had always been good at performance. He had received training in the art of giving people exactly what they wanted so that they would give in return. There could be nothing more important to him right now than charming this shy, kindly, awkward boy. \par
\tab \'93Ranger Pyman!\'94 he said as he stood up. \'93It\'92s good to see you again.\'94\par
\tab \'93I--I brought you something to eat,\'94 Pyman said quite unnecessarily as he set down the tray on the table. \'93Hope you like it.\'94\par
\tab \'93I\'92m sure I will,\'94 Verick said, crossing to the table. \par
\tab Pyman turned back toward the door, but Verick did not want him to leave, not just yet. \'93Wait!\'94 Verick said. \'93I\'92m in here alone all day. Do you have to leave right away?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I guess not,\'94 Pyman said. \'93I--I can stay a minute or two.\'94\par
\tab \'93Wonderful,\'94 Verick said, offering up his warmest smile. \'93Sit, sit, take a moment,\'94 he said. \'93With everything that\'92s been going on, you Rangers must be run right off your feet. \'94\par
\tab Pyman sat down on the edge of the chair nearest the door, and Verick sat down opposite him, trying to be encouraging without scaring the poor boy off. \'93I guess that\'92s true,\'94 Pyman said. \'93Things have been pretty busy. Seems like the whole world\'92s gone crazy.\'94\par
\tab \'93You wouldn\'92t know it in here,\'94 Verick said. \'93Nothing but peace and quiet.\'94\par
\tab \'93Sure ain\'92t like that out there,\'94 Pyman said, gesturing to indicate the outside world. \'93We\'92ve been run off our feet ever since the Governor got killed--\'94 \par
\tab \'93The Governor was what?\'94 Verick said, corning out of his seat. \par
\tab \'93Oh! Oh, my!\'94 Pyman said, clearly shocked and alarmed. \'93I wasn\'92t supposed to say anything! We weren\'92t to tell you about that. I--I can\'92t say anything more. \'94 Pyman got up abruptly. \'93I\'92m sorry. Real sorry. I can\'92t say nothing more. Please don\'92t tell \'91em I told you. \'94 He pulled open the door, stepped around the robot sentry, and slammed the door shut behind him. \par
\tab Verick watched the door, his heart pounding, his fists clenched. No. No. Calm yourself; he told himself. He opened his hands, rubbed his hand over his bald scalp, and willed his heart to stop pounding. Calm yourself; he told himself again. He sat down and let out a deep breath. \par
\tab Well, there it was. They had told him what it was all about. \par
\tab But what was he going to do about it now? \par
