\tab Alvar Kresh stared, unseeing, out the window as Donald flew him back to the Residence. He was thinking. Thinking hard. Strange bedfellows, police work and politics. It would be a real challenge to satisfy the demands of both, but he was starting to realize that the two were so intertwined that he had no choice. Clues, false leads, ideas, theories, snatches of conversation, and random bits of information seemed to be swirling around in his head. Grieg with a blaster hole in his chest. Grieg\'92s simulated image assuring Kresh he was all right. Telmhock\'92s muddled attempt to tell Kresh he was the Governor. Kresh nearly tripping over a dead SPR to get to Grieg\'92s office. The ghostly image of Bissal captured by the integrator as he headed toward the lower-level storage room. \par
\tab Half of it was no doubt vital information, while the other half was unimportant. But which half was which? He closed his eyes and tried to concentrate. No, don\'92t concentrate. Relax. Relax. Let it come on its own terms. Don\'92t expect the answer to come on schedule. It will arrive on its own terms, invited or not. There was, he told himself, no sense trying to force the solution to arrive--\par
\tab And that was the exact moment the light came on. Yes. That had to be it. He needed proof, he needed to pull it all together--but yes. He knew. He knew. \par
\par
\tab Donald 111, convinced that his master had fallen asleep, tried to land the aircar as gently as he could. But, not for the first time, Alvar Kresh surprised his personal robot. He was out of the car before Donald was out of his seat, looking quite awake--in fact quite energetic and determined. Donald made a mental note to remember that there were times when humans actually did get some thinking done with their eyes shut, even if most thinking was no more than an excuse for a nap. \par
\tab \'93I want Caliban and Prospero in my office,\'94 Kresh said, walking toward the entrance, his eyes straight ahead. \'93 And I want them there now.\'94\par
\tab \'93Yes, sir,\'94 Donald said, hurrying to catch up with him. \'93I will bring them up directly. \'94 Once I have you safely inside the secured interior of the Residence, Donald thought. There was still danger everywhere. \par
\tab \'93Good,\'94 Kresh said as he walked through the main entrance. \'93I have one thing to do first. Something that might take a bit of time. Wait for me in the Governor\'92s office.\'94\par
\tab \'93Yes, sir,\'94 Donald said, more than a bit surprised. He knew all of Alvar Kresh\'92s moods, and he knew this one especially well. It was Alvar Kresh on the hunt, Alvar Kresh closing in for the kill. But how? And who? Donald hurried down to the improvised cell where Caliban and Prospero were being held. He had been ahead of Kresh in solving a case now and then, and well behind him on many occasions. But he had never been this far back. Did Kresh have the perpetrator in his sights, even before Donald had so much as a guess at the list of suspects? \par
\tab Donald gestured for the guard robot to unlock the cell door, and stepped inside even before the door was fully open. Prospero and Caliban were both sitting on the floor of the cell. \'93Get up,\'94 Donald said, not even trying to keep the excitement and satisfaction out of his voice. \'93The Governor wants you upstairs. \'94 The two of them got to their feet, a bit uncertainly. Donald was glad to see their discomfiture. It gave him real pleasure to order these two around. Did this summons mean that Kresh had decided the two pseudo-robots were indeed the guilty parties? That would be pleasure and triumph unbounded. \par
\par
\tab Kresh was not in the room when Donald and his two prisoners arrived, a minute or two later. Donald gestured for the two of them to stand in the center of the floor, while he retired to a wall niche. Waiting was not generally much of a hardship to a robot. Robots spent a great deal of their existence waiting for humans to arrive, or for humans to leave, or for humans to make up their minds about an order. Nonetheless, Donald found the wait for Kresh to be almost unbearable. Something was going on. He knew it. He knew it. \par
\tab The three robots waited in silence for sixteen minutes and twenty-three seconds, according to Donald\'92s internal chronometer. And then the doors slid open, and Kresh strode into the room. He was carrying an opaque evidence storage box. He set the box down on the desk, and then turned to Caliban and Prospero. He spoke right to the point, without any sort of preamble. \'93I want to know,\'94 said Kresh, \'93exactly what transpired between you and Tierlaw Verick. Exactly. I want your precise words, his and yours.\'94\par
\tab \'93Do you mean on the night of Governor Grieg\'92s death?\'94 Caliban asked. \par
\tab \'93When else have you met with him?\'94 Kresh demanded. \par
\tab \'93Never,\'94 Caliban said. \'93Never at any time before or since. \'94\par
\tab \'93Then tell me what happened the one time you did meet,\'94 Kresh said. \par
\tab \'93Well, it was a rather brief exchange,\'94 Caliban said, clearly still rather mystified. \'93We were waiting by the door--\'94 \par
\tab \'93Just the two of you?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93No one else?\'94 \par
\tab \'93No one else around at all,\'94 Caliban said. \'93If you are hoping for some sort of witness besides Prospero to corroborate my statement, I\'92m afraid there was no one. Prospero and I were waiting by the door when Tierlaw came out. He seemed rather upset about something, and also rather surprised to see us there. He said, \'91I thought I was the end of the line tonight,\'92 and laughed. \'94\par
\tab \'93Laughed rather nervously, I thought,\'94 Prospero said. Caliban nodded. \'93Yes, he was nervous. He spoke rather loudly, and seemed rather agitated. I spoke to him and said, \'91My friend and I were a last-minute addition. \'92 \par
\tab \'93He replied by saying, \'91Well, you\'92ll learn about all sorts of changes in there. Everything is decided. No one will be in control, and you lot are going to kingdom come. We\'92ve all had it. Grieg just told me. It\'92s allover now. \'92\'94\par
\tab \'93And then what?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab \'93Then nothing,\'94 Prospero said. \'93He turned away and stomped down the hall. Caliban and I were somewhat taken aback by what he said, but we had no chance to discuss it. The door to Grieg\'92s office opened, and we went inside for our meeting. That was all that transpired between us. \'94\par
\tab \'93I see,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Very well. That is all. The two of you may go.\'94\par
\tab \'93Shall we return to our cell?\'94 Prospero asked. \par
\tab \'93Do precisely as you please,\'94 Kresh snapped. \'93Isn\'92t that what your damned Fourth Law says to do? Just leave me, and remain inside the Residence. I will want you back later. I strongly advise that you do not attempt to leave.\'94\par
\tab \'93Of course not,\'94 Caliban said. \'93Neither of us wishes to commit suicide.\'94\par
\tab \'93Really?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93You have an odd way of showing it. Now get out.\'94\par
\tab Donald watched the two pseudo-robots leave, greatly confused. Their account of their exchange with Tierlaw Verick was at variance with Verick\'92s account, but given Verick\'92s hostility to robots, it was only to be expected that he would be rude to them. \par
\tab More seriously, Governor Kresh seemed to be taking the pseudo-robots\'92 accounts at face value--though both Prospero and Caliban were capable of lying. For a moment, Donald debated bringing that point to Kresh\'92s attention. But there was something in the fierce concentration of the man\'92s expression that made Donald believe that would be a serious mistake. No. Governor Alvar Kresh was a man who knew exactly what he was doing. \par
\tab And one thing he was doing was paying no attention whatsoever to Donald. Humans often forgot there were robots about, seeing everything that happened. Donald always appreciated such moments, as they gave him an unparalleled chance to observe human behavior. He watched, motionless, from his wall niche as Kresh pulled a piece of paper out of Grieg\'92s archaic desk set, fumbled for a moment with one of Grieg\'92s strange old pens, and then set to writing. He seemed to be making up a list of some sort. \par
\tab He finished writing, set down the pen, and considered the paper for a moment. Then he turned to the comm panel next to the desk and punched in a number manually. The screen lit up, and Donald could see Justen Devray on the screen. \'93Get in here,\'94 Kresh said, and cut the connection before Devray had a chance to speak. \par
\tab Kresh picked up the piece of paper and got up from behind the desk. He began pacing the room, going back and forth, back and forth, at a rather deliberate pace, his full attention on the paper. He went back to the desk and picked up the pen again. He scratched something out, and wrote something else Ill. \par
\tab The door annunciator chimed, and Kresh pushed a button on his desk. \par
\tab The door opened, and Justen Devray came in. \par
\tab \'93Well, Justen,\'94 Kresh said. \'93It would appear I have a job for my Rangers. \'94 He handed Devray the paper. \'93Contact Cinta Melloy and coordinate with the 888. Pull these people in, Justen. All of them. Now. And I want you and Melloy here as well. With you it\'92s an order--but you can extend my invitation to Cinta. I have a feeling she\'92ll accept.\'94\par
\tab Devray looked at the list and shook his head. \'93Maybe Melloy will want to come,\'94 he said. \'93But some of these people aren\'92t going to like it,\'94 he said. \par
\tab \'93Just get them,\'94 Kresh said. \'93I want them all here, in this office, and I want them here in two hours.\'94\par
\tab Devray nodded, and then, after a moment, remembered to salute. \'93Yes, sir,\'94 he said. And with that he turned and left, Kresh using the door button to let him out. \par
\tab Kresh watched Devray leave, waited a minute, and then followed after, using the ID scanner plate by the door to make it open. Kresh stopped and examined something in the door frame on his way out. Whatever he found seemed to please him, and he went on his way. The room sensed that there were no humans about, and faded the lights down. \par
\tab Leaving Donald alone in the dark. In more ways than one. He wanted to follow, to stay with his master--but no. Alone. Let him work it out alone. The Governor could always summon Donald if he needed him. \par
\par
\tab \'93I have to go, Gubber,\'94 Tonya said. \par
\tab \'93You could protest it!\'94 Gubber said. \'93Claim diplomatic immunity. Refuse to go. It was bad enough the way Caliban just vanished and ended up in jail. I barely knew him, and it scared me half to death. If it happened to you, I couldn\'92t bear it. Don\'92t go. Don\'92t let them get you. Stay.\'94\par
\tab \'93That could only make things worse,\'94 Tonya said, her tone far less calm than her words. \'93I know this hasn\'92t been easy for you. But I promise you it will be over after tonight. I don\'92t know why Kresh wants me, but he does. I don\'92t know if I\'92m a suspect, or a witness, or if he just wants to chat about terraforming. He wants me, and I have to go.\'94\par
\tab \'93But why?\'94 \par
\tab Tonya took a step or two toward the door, then turned and looked back. Logically, she knew it was going to be all right. Nothing was going to happen. But she had no such confidence on the emotional level. Fear was loose in the world. \'93I have to go,\'94 she said, \'93because we live on this world, you and I. We live here, and Alvar Kresh might be the only man who can save it. If I fight this, with all the legal ways I might, that can\'92t be good for him. \par
\tab \'93And as of today\'92s announcement, what is bad for Alvar Kresh is good for Simcor Beddle.\'94\par
\par
\tab Kresh tried to relax. He took a quick shower, changed into fresh clothes, had a quick bite to eat--and tried to settle himself down. He found the Residence library and selected a booktape to read, more or less at random. He sat there, with the words scrolling past his eyes, not taking in more than one word in ten of the story. \par
\tab Calmly. Slowly. He started the tape over a half-dozen times before he gave up. He could not concentrate on anything else but the case. Because now, all of a sudden, he had a case. \par
\tab He had more than that. He had the answer. He was as certain of that as he had been of anything in his life. But for all of that, it would still be easy--very, very easy--for him to make a mistake. Kresh set the tape aside, and thought it through again, and again. \par
\tab Justen Devray came in the library almost precisely two hours after Kresh had sent him off. \par
\tab \'93They\'92re all here,\'94 he said. \'93Waiting for you. \'94\par
\tab \'93Good,\'94 said Kresh. \'93Good. Then\'92s let go see them.\'94\par
\tab Justen led Kresh up the stairs to the Governor\'92s office--to his office--and ushered him inside. Kresh took a deep breath and faced a roomful of people who had to be thinking they were all suspects in Grieg\'92s murder. In the Governor\'92s murder, he told himself. And you\'92re the Governor now. Kresh glanced to the wall niches, and was relieved to see Donald there. Nice to know there was someone here who was utterly, unquestionably, on Kresh\'92s side. \par
\tab Kresh looked around the room at all of them. Leving, Devray, Welton, Melloy, Beddle, Verick, Phrost, Caliban, Prospero. The humans among them looked edgy, upset, nervous. Even the two robots looked a bit ill at ease. As well they might. \'93Fredda, you\'92re here because I assumed you\'92d want to see the end of it. You\'92re in the clear. As for the rest of you,\'94 he said, \'93I have a problem. A very simple problem, but one with no simple solution. And my simple problem is this: It has come to my attention that you\'92re all guilty.\'94\par
\tab It took a full ten seconds of stunned silence before they started shouting their denials. \par
