\'93ALL GUILTY OF different crimes,\'94 Kresh said. \'93But guilty just the same. You were the one that did it, Cinta.\'94\par
\tab Cinta Melloy looked startled. \'93Me? Are you out of your mind? I might have a little dirt under my nails, but I didn\'92t kill anyone.\'94\par
\tab \'93No,\'94 Kresh agreed, \'93you didn\'92t. But you were the one who gave me the clue I needed. \'93 And it did no harm at all to rattle you and everyone el. \\\'94e in the room by saying it that way, Kresh thought. \par
\tab \'93What clue was that?\'94 said Cinta. \par
\tab \'93At the fire,\'94 Kresh replied. \'93You said something about not being invited, and showing up anyway. \'94\par
\tab \'93That\'92s your big clue?\'94 Cinta asked. \par
\tab \'93That\'92s my big clue.\'94\par
\tab \'93I hardly see how those words are the basis for accusing anyone of murder,\'94 Prospero said. \par
\tab \'93Oh, you and Caliban don\'92t need to worry about murder charges either,\'94 Kresh said. \'93You are here precisely because I no longer suspect you. You have cleared yourselves of all charges--aside from attempted blackmail--without anyone realizing it.\'94\par
\tab \'93How so?\'94 Caliban asked. \par
\tab \'93By not connecting the term \'91Valhalla\'92 to a garbled rendition of its meaning, \'93 Kresh said \par
\tab \'93Alvar--Governor Kresh--for stars\'92 sake stop playing games!\'94 Fredda said. \'93Just tell us whatever it is you have to tell us.\'94\par
\tab \'93Be patient, Fredda,\'94 Kresh said. \'93We\'92ll get there. \'94 He turned to the robots. \'93Caliban, Prospero, you told Donald. Now tell me--and I would urge you not to hold anything back, if you value your survival. When you came here, to this office, to meet Grieg, what was your plan?\'94 \par
\tab \'93To threaten him with the simultaneous exposure of every scandal on this planet if he decided to exterminate the New Law robots,\'94 Prospero said. \par
\tab \'93And you made this threat?\'94 Kresh asked, \par
\tab \'93We did, couching it in the most polite terms possible, \'93 Prospero said. \'93However, he did not seem at all upset or perturbed by it. \'94\par
\tab \'93I would go further than that,\'94 Caliban said. \'93He seemed rather amused by the idea, as if he didn\'92t for a moment think we would carry it out.\'94\par
\tab \'93And would you have?\'94 Kresh asked. \par
\tab The two robots looked at each other, and then Caliban spoke. \'93We were to meet the next day and begin preparing our materials for release,\'94 Caliban said. \'93Then we heard that Grieg was dead, and of course canceled the plan. \'94\par
\tab \'93How did you get your information. \'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93Slowly,\'94 Prospero said. \'93Gradually. The rustbacking network is full of tipsters and rumormongers. And there is an old axiom to the effect that those who would seek the truth should follow the money. We studied a great number of transactions, legal and otherwise. They taught us much.\'94\par
\tab \'93Tell me some of what was in that material,\'94 Kresh said. \'93No, better still, let me tell you. You had proof that Simcor \par
\tab Beddle here was taking Settler money--perhaps without knowing that he was taking it. \'94\par
\tab \'93But I--\'94 Beddle began. \par
\tab \'93Quiet, Beddle,\'94 Kresh said. \'93You\'92re not Governor yet. Right now you\'92ll speak when spoken to. \'94 He turned back to the robots. \'93You also had proof that Sero Phrost and Tonya Welton were in the smuggling business together. \'94 Another little stir of reaction, but Phrost and Welton both had the sense to keep quiet. \'93Proof that Tierlaw Verick\'92s bidding group had been bribing government officials. Verick was also linked to the rustbackers--along with half the planet, it seems to me, but I doubt you would divulge that little tidbit.\'94\par
\tab \'93Now just a moment,\'94 Verick protested. \'93I did no such--\'94 \par
\tab \'93Quiet, Verick. \'94 Kresh said. \'93And you also had proof that Commander Devray and Captain Melloy here were both in possession of proof of criminal acts in high places and were not acting upon that information.\'94\par
\tab Devray and Melloy seemed about to protest, but Kresh cut them off. \'93Not a word, either of you,\'94 he said, with enough steel in his voice to silence both of them. \'93Both of you did have such information, and both of you informed Governor Grieg of it. Justen, you told him about Tierlaw\'92s bribery, and, Cinta, you told him about Sero Phrost smuggling Settler hardware and passing the proceeds to the Ironheads. I\'92ve seen Grieg\'92s files. I know. Grieg didn\'92t do anything about the information, either, for the same reasons you both kept quiet.\'94\par
\tab \'93And what reason would that be?\'94 Phrost demanded, daring to speak. \par
\tab \'93He was afraid that if he pulled on one thread, everything else would unravel, \'93 Kresh said. \'93 Arrest Sero Phrost, and Phrost would implicate Tonya Welton. Grieg needed Welton\'92s support. Grieg also knew the Spacer bid on the control system would probably collapse without Phrost. Arrest Verick, and Grieg knew he would lose the Settler bid on the system.\'94\par
\tab Devray looked confused. \'93But wait a second. The robots just said that Grieg didn\'92t seem to care if they blew the lid off everything.\'94\par
\tab \'93Exactly,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Because, on the night he died, he knew it didn\'92t matter anymore. He had made his final decisions about the control system, and about the New Law robots. He was going to announce them the next day. What the robots were doing was threatening to sweep all his enemies out of the way, and threatening to do so at the exact moment he no longer needed to keep his enemies happy. \'93 Kresh turned toward the robots. \'93He couldn\'92t smear his opponents without making himself look very, very bad. But you two could. You were threatening him with the biggest favor of his political career.\'94\par
\tab \'93It couldn\'92t all be good for him,\'94 Melloy protested. \'93With that much mudslinging set loose, he would have gotten messed up a little himself. Someone would have tried to fight back.\'94\par
\tab \'93Fight back at who? The robots?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93They were the ones about to release the material, not Grieg. But even if you\'92re right--and you probably are--Grieg would have accepted any amount of damage to his prestige if it meant getting rid of Simcor Beddle.\'94\par
\tab \'93And you are saying Grieg no longer cared because he had made his decisions,\'94 Caliban said. \'93Might I ask what those decisions were, and if you intend to abide by them?\'94 \par
\tab \'93I do not wish to answer either of those questions, just at the moment,\'94 Kresh said. \'93I have a rather cryptic note Grieg made to himself. I believe it contains his answer. But I don\'92t need to decipher the note. Tierlaw Verick here has done it for me.\'94\par
\tab \'93He told you what Grieg had decided?\'94 Fredda asked. \'93When? I never heard it.\'94\par
\tab Tierlaw Verick opened his mouth to protest again, but then thought better of it. \par
\tab \'93Good thinking, Verick,\'94 Kresh said. \'93If I were you, I wouldn\'92t say one thing more.\'94\par
\tab \'93But what did he say?\'94 Fredda asked. \'93What did I miss?\'94\par
\tab \'93You heard everything I did,\'94 Kresh said. \'93And his reactions told me what Grieg\'92s decisions were. \'94\par
\tab \'93Then he was telling the truth,\'94 Caliban said. \'93When he came out of Grieg\'92s office, he told Prospero and myself we were going to kingdom come. An archaic reference to the hereafter. He was telling us that Grieg had decided to destroy the New Law robots.\'94\par
\tab \'93And that scared the hell out of you, and you went into Grieg full of bluff and bluster and threatened him before he even had a chance to tell you he intended to destroy you. \'94 Kresh shook his head. \'93A mistake. A very serious mistake on your part. \'94\par
\tab \'93A mistake in what way?\'94 Caliban asked. \par
\tab \'93And you claim to be high-function beings,\'94 Donald said, speaking for the first time as he stepped down from his wall niche. \'93If you were true robots, human behavior would have been your constant study, and you would not have erred. Can you truly understand so little of human nature?\'94 \par
\tab \'93What do you mean?\'94 Caliban asked. \'93Governor Kresh, is he speaking with your authority?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Donald is speaking for himself,\'94 Kresh said, \'93but he\'92s getting it right for all of that. Go on, Donald.\'94\par
\tab \'93It might be logical to expect Governor Grieg to tell you his decision in the same way no matter what that decision was, but that is not the human way. It does not account for the Governor\'92s personality. To expect him to act in such a way takes no account of the emotions of pleasure in bringing good news, or the embarrassment and sorrow humans feel when reporting bad news for which they are responsible. It would not be in Grieg\'92s character to call you into his office and tell you he intended to wipe you out. You would have found out by seeing it on the news, or by written notice--or by getting a blaster shot through the head.\'94\par
\tab \'93What are you saying?\'94 Prospero demanded. \par
\tab \'93That you should have known his decision would be in your favor as soon as he asked to see you face-to-face,\'94 Donald said. \par
\tab \'93And when Verick told you that you were going to kingdom come, he was just telling what Grieg had told him,\'94 \par
\tab Kresh said. \'93Except he got it wrong. Grieg had been looking for a third way, some solution between tolerating the current intolerable state of affairs and extermination. And he found it. He found it and told it to Verick.\'94\par
\tab \'93I still do not understand,\'94 Prospero said. \'93But now I do,\'94 Caliban said, sitting stock-still, staring straight ahead. \'93Now I do. Valhalla. Grieg told Verick he was sending all the New Law robots to Valhalla. To someone living on Inferno, that is a place name. It is the place to which all New Law robots wish to escape, a hidden place as far away from human interference as possible. But Verick thought the Governor was speaking in metaphor, speaking of the old Earth legend from which the name is derived. Valhalla, the hall of the gods, where those who have died in battle will live. The afterlife. Kingdom come. \'94\par
\tab \'93So you threatened the man who had found a way to save you,\'94 Kresh said. \'93 And threatened to do the thing he would most love to have done, but dared not do himself. And, at a guess, that appealed to his sense of humor. So he told you to leave and not come back, hoping to have the public hear all about friend Beddle\'92s finances in the next day or so. The irony is that you had no motive for Grieg\'92s murder, even if you thought you did.\'94\par
\tab \'93So you still have every reason to suspect us,\'94 Caliban said. \par
\tab \'93On the contrary, I am absolutely certain you two had nothing to do with the murder of Chanto Grieg,\'94 Kresh said. \par
\tab \'93It sounds like you\'92ve got this whole thing figured out,\'94 Melloy said, a bit grumpily. \par
\tab \'93I do,\'94 Kresh said. \par
\tab \'93So tell us about it,\'94 Cinta said. \'93If that wouldn\'92t be too much trouble.\'94\par
\tab \'93Too much trouble was exactly what it was,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Fredda pointed that out. The plan was too intricate, too theatrical. That\'92s what I should have seen from the start. The plan had too many people in it, too many moving parts, too many bits of complicated coordination and timing--especially with someone as unreliable and plainly expendable as Ottley Bissal at the center of it. The plan required an assassin willing to do what he was told if the paycheck was big enough, someone willing to perform a despicable act--and yet someone foolish enough to trust the plotter who intended to kill him. Those are not job requirements that produce quality applicants. Whoever took on the job was bound to be someone who made mistakes, who got sloppy. Someone like Bissal. That should have told me something. It should have told me the plan wouldn\'92t work. And sure enough, it didn\'92t.\'94\par
\tab \'93But Grieg was killed,\'94 Fredda protested. \par
\tab \'93Not in the way the mastermind intended,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Not in the way Tierlaw Verick planned.\'94\par
\tab Verick jumped up, and was halfway to Kresh before Donald could intercept him. Donald pinned the man\'92s arms to his side and dragged him back to his seat. \'93It was the basic problem of the whole case,\'94 Kresh said. \'93We knew, even once Fredda spotted Bissal, that we didn\'92t have the real killer. Bissal was so obviously someone else\'92s creature. But whoever had sent him--and sent all the other conspirators along--had done a good job of staying hidden. It could have been anyone with access to the right sort of technology, and the wrong sort of people. It could have been anyone in this room. It could even have been me, I suppose. But it was you, Verick.\'94\par
\tab \'93You\'92re crazy, Kresh,\'94 Verick half shouted. \'93How could I have done it? I didn\'92t even know Grieg was dead until one of the guards on my room told me.\'94\par
\tab \'93And it must have been a relief when the guard made that slip,\'94 Kresh said. \'93You could stop acting. It made it that much less likely that you would make a slip. Good as you were, you knew you could not keep it up forever. And you were good. You even managed to fool Donald\'92s lie-detector system--and that requires some impressive training. Our files said you dabbled in theatrics. We did not know just how good an actor you were. The trouble was you\'92d made your slip already. One you couldn\'92t avoid.\'94\par
\tab \'93And what slip might that be?\'94 Verick demanded. \par
\tab \'93You said there were two robots standing in the hallway when he came out of this office. Not three.\'94\par
\tab \'93But there were only two,\'94 Caliban protested. \'93There was only Prospero and myself.\'94\par
\tab \'93But then where the devil was the door sentry robot?\'94 Kresh demanded. \'93It was there, standing in front of the door, shot through the chest, when I checked the upper floor after discovering Grieg\'92s body. SPRs on other duties move around, but a door sentry robot does not go off post. Not unless it received orders to do so, from someone in authority to give orders.\'94\par
\tab \'93So Tierlaw didn\'92t notice a robot,\'94 Cinta said, who seemed to have taken it upon herself to defend her fellow Settler. \'93So what? You Spacers always ignore robots. That\'92s not enough to convict a man of murder. \'94\par
\tab \'93Tierlaw is not a Spacer, but a Settler,\'94 Donald said. \'93He has a pronounced aversion to robots, and very definitely noticed the other two standing outside the door. He gave a detailed and accurate description of Prospero and Caliban.\'94\par
\tab \'93So what are you saying?\'94 Devray said. \par
\tab \'93I\'92m saying that Tierlaw ordered the Sapper, the SPR sentry robot, to be out of position. But a Sapper won\'92t take orders from just anyone. He--or a subordinate, more likely--must have gotten to the robot sometime before and used some rather sophisticated order giving to convince the sentry that orders from him, from Tierlaw, took precedence over everything else, even guarding Grieg. \'94\par
\tab \'93Is that possible?\'94 Devray asked. \par
\tab \'93Yes,\'94 Fredda said. \'93If the SPR did not believe Grieg was in any particular danger, so that First Law potential was reduced, and if it saw Tierlaw as its owner, thus enhancing Second Law potential, then yes, Tierlaw could have given the order for the sentry to clear off and come back later. \'94\par
\tab \'93It\'92s thin,\'94 Cinta said. \'93And I don\'92t see what it has to do with anything. \'94\par
\tab \'93It is thin,\'94 Kresh admitted. \'93I knew that as soon as I figured it out. I knew I needed proof--and I found it. But there is more. Caliban and Prospero were witnesses that Tierlaw came out the inner door to Grieg\'92s office. After-hours visitors to his office always used the outer side door. But Tierlaw needed to let Bissal in. So he got Grieg to open the inner door somehow.\'94\par
\tab \'93But he did not let Bissal in. He let us in,\'94 Caliban said. \par
\tab \'93And why would he let Bissal see his face?\'94 Cinta demanded. \par
\tab \'93He wouldn\'92t let Bissal see him,\'94 Kresh said, heading over to his desk. \'93He didn\'92t. \'94 He unsealed the evidence box and pulled out a pocket communicator, and a thin piece of black metal in the shape of a flattened triangle. \'93I found these in your room, Verick, the one you stayed in the night of the murder. You\'92re good at hiding things. The room had been searched twice before I went over it. But I knew what I was looking for--and that makes a great deal of difference. And before you can protest that these were planted, a Crime Scene Observer robot witnessed the search and recorded it.\'94\par
\tab \'93I recognize the communicator, but what\'92s the other thing?\'94 Fredda asked. \par
\tab \'93It\'92s one of these,\'94 Kresh said. He went to the inner door of the office and used the scanner panel to open it. Once it was open, he took the piece of metal and set it in the frame of the door. It stayed there of its own accord. Kresh stepped back, and the door closed--but not all the way. There was a barely discernible crack between the frame and the sliding door. Kresh got his fingers into the crack and pulled. It took a bit of effort, but he managed to get the door open. Kresh took the door wedge out of the frame, crossed the room, and put it back in the evidence box. \par
\tab \'93Grieg was supposed to be killed right here,\'94 he said. \'93In this office. Verick would set the door wedge on his way out--with a little practice, they\'92re easy to set surreptitiously. Tierlaw would order the office door sentry robot back into position, and then signal Bissal, waiting in the basement, to turn on the range restrictor signal that would deactivate the SPR robots. Then Tierlaw could simply walk out of the house, unobserved, while Bissal came up out of the basement, came into the office, and shot Grieg. Bissal would remove the door wedge, and go on with the rest of the plot--destroying the robots to hide the restrictors, and then escaping to the warehouse, where he would hide until things cooled off--except the food left for him there was poisoned. He must have died within a few hours of Grieg.\'94\par
\tab \'93That\'92s the craziest plan I\'92ve ever heard,\'94 Cinta protested. \'93It could never work.\'94\par
\tab \'93And it didn\'92t, \'93 Devray said. \'93It was crazy, Cinta, but think what we would have found if it had worked. Grieg dead behind a locked door, fifty wrecked security robots, and an assassin who simply vanishes without a trace. A few days later, a warehouse blows up and bums down, and no one ever thinks to connect the two. Things are bad enough as they are. People are scared. Just imagine the panic, the chaos, if the murder had been as smooth, as perfect as it was supposed to be.\'94\par
\tab \'93But things went wrong,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Things went wrong. The two robots are waiting outside the door, so you can\'92t set the door wedge, could you, Verick? And you couldn\'92t use your communicator in front of the robots, either. So you slip into a vacant room and contact Bissal from there, telling him what had gone wrong. You tell him to go to plan B, killing Grieg in his room. \par
\tab \'93But then you realize that you couldn\'92t leave the vacant room. At a guess, one of the sentries on random patrol takes up a post in the hall. If you leave the room, that would raise the alarm. So you had to stay there, in that room, until the robots left, until you heard Grieg go to bed. You could signal Bissal. Then Bissal activates the range restrictor signal, and the sentries go dead. But even then you can\'92t leave, because Bissal has come up into the house. Suppose he saw you, and knew who you were? He\'92d have a hold over you. Suppose he tried to blackmail you instead of going off to eat his poison at the warehouse? No, you could not risk that. So you decide to wait until you heard Bissal leave the house. \par
\tab \'93But Bissal had wasted most of his blaster\'92s charge, and he realizes he isn\'92t going to have enough power left to be able to shoot all the robots. So Bissal decides to remove the restrictors from half of them by hand, and it takes forever. At long last he is done, and destroys the blaster and the Trojan robot in the basement, and heads off on his way. At last you can go. \par
\tab \'93Except suddenly you can see the sky is full of police vehicles of one sort or another. The police have discovered Huthwitz\'92s body. You still can\'92t leave. Then I arrive, and rush up the stairs. Grieg has been discovered long before you expected. \par
\tab \'93Suddenly you hear new footsteps in the halls and realize they are searching room to room. You hide under the bed or something during the first, cursory search. But you know they will search again, or at the very least stumble across you. You can\'92t hide in the one room forever. So you very cleverly brazen it out. \par
\tab \'93You hide the incriminating door wedge and communicator, and then dress in the pajamas left in the room. Maybe you can talk your way out of it. It\'92s a long shot, but the only chance you have. You wander out into the hallway, and pretend you\'92re a house guest who\'92s slept through the whole thing. Donald here snatches you up. And you very nearly got away with it. Until Cinta Melloy here decided to look into whether Grieg ever had overnight guests--and found out he never did. We never thought to check the other side of the point, by the way. Did you have a hotel reservation in Limbo City? If--or rather when--we do find one, how will you explain it?\'94 \par
\tab Verick opened his mouth and shut it again, and swallowed hard, and then at last the words came out. \'93 And what was my motive supposed to be in this lunatic scheme?\'94 he asked, his voice tight and calm and strained. \'93What was all this supposed to accomplish for me?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Profit,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Huge profit. Money. Not a motive we Spacers cops are used to. I didn\'92t even consider it at first. Money hasn\'92t meant much for a while, though it\'92s started to again. You went into that meeting with Kresh to find out if he had accepted your control system design. If he told you he had chosen your system, you would not signal Bissal, there would be no attack, and Bissal would slip away when he could. If Grieg told you Phrost had the job--well then, a terrifying assassination of the Governor might well sow just enough distrust of robots that a new Governor would not go with a robot design--or else it might be easier to bribe the new incumbent. You might even already know Beddle wasn\'92t above taking Settler money. You might even have had some dealings with him. Did you offer Grieg a bribe, by the way? He was half expecting that you would. \'94\par
\tab Verick screamed and lunged, and Donald had to struggle a bit to hold him down. \par
\tab \'93I\'92ll take that as a yes,\'94 said Governor Kresh. \'93Commander Devray, perhaps you could take this man into custody.\'94\par
