\par
 \'93AND THAT IS THAT,\'94 Kresh said, after Melloy and Welton were gone and Devray and his Rangers took a sobbing, hysterical Tierlaw Verick away. \'93You two are free to go,\'94 he said to Beddle and Phrost. \par
\tab \'93But what about the charges against us?\'94 Beddle asked. \par
\tab \'93What charges?\'94 Kresh asked. \'93No one has filed any that I\'92m aware of. I don\'92t intend to. \'94\par
\tab \'93That\'92s very generous of you, Governor,\'94 said Sero Phrost. \par
\tab \'93The hell it is,\'94 Kresh said. \'93I think I can do more damage to the two of you by letting you stay in the public eye. After all, everything that was said in this room today is bound to reach the public, somehow. Someone is bound to leak something--wouldn\'92t you agree, Prospero? Stories--at the very least rumors--about smuggling and bribery and money laundering are bound to float to the surface. I have a feeling that Tonya Welton is going to be able to explain away a lot of things you two can\'92t. Oh, and Beddle, I\'92m looking forward to your announcement for Governor. It should be an exciting campaign.\'94\par
\tab \'93But I--I--\'94\par
\tab \'93Quiet, Simcor,\'94 Phrost said. \'93Don\'92t give him any more ammunition. Let\'92s get out of here. \'94 The two men got up and left, and Kresh was glad to push the door button and get them out of his sight. \par
\tab \'93They\'92re down now, but they won\'92t stay down,\'94 said Fredda Leving. \'93You know that, don\'92t you?\'94 \par
\tab \'93Oh, yes, of course,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Phrost still has a lot of friends, and a lot of money, and there are plenty of true believers in the Ironheads who\'92ll forgive Beddle anything. But this way, they\'92re damaged goods. If I brought charges against them, they could accuse me of politicizing the courts, or something. Better to let the rumors leak out and do their damage.\'94\par
\tab Kresh stood up and stretched and looked thoughtful for a moment. \'93 You know, I\'92ve just had an odd thought, \'93 he said. \'93Of all the cases I\'92ve ever dealt with that concerned robots, I think this is the first one I\'92ve ever had where the Three Laws weren\'92t involved somewhere in the solution.\'94\par
\tab \'93But they were, Governor Kresh,\'94 said Caliban. \'93They were involved most intimately.\'94\par
\tab \'93In what way?\'94\par
\tab \'93 \'91A robot may not injure a human being or, through inaction, allow a human being to come to harm,\'92 \'93 Caliban said, repeating the First Law. \'93Verick relied most heavily upon Spacer faith in that statement. In a sense, he set fifty robots with an incomplete First Law loose in the Governor\'92s Residence. They were shut down, turned off--inactive. Through inaction, they allowed a human being to come to harm. \'94\par
\tab \'93It is an interesting feature of the First Law,\'94 Donald said. \'93I myself experienced a most unpleasant reaction when I realized that I could have saved Grieg if I had been with him--even though it would have been impossible for me to be with him while I was performing my normal duties. No doubt there are many human beings in the universe who are being injured at this very moment. Though logically I realize there is nothing I can do about it, I must admit I find it a most disturbing notion. And it is part and parcel of the First Law. The Law is couched in such strong and solid absolutes that it cannot possibly match up with the greys and uncertainties and limitations of everyday life.\'94\par
\tab \'93Donald,\'94 Fredda said. \'93That almost sounds like a criticism of the absolute nature of the Three Laws.\'94\par
\tab \'93By no means, Dr. Leving. It is a criticism of the disorderly nature of everyday life.\'94\par
\tab Fredda laughed and turned to Caliban. \'93 And what about you, Caliban? What about the Laws and you? Have you learned more on that score?\'94 \par
\tab \'93A year ago, my accidental escape from the lab, and the subsequent pursuit caused me to integrate my own internal Law--to protect myself. But if I pursued self-preservation at all cost, Prospero and I would have fled Purgatory. I have no doubt that the ensuing search for us would have cost many New Law robots their lives. I believe that I have integrated a new internal Law set--Cooperate for the greater good. Protect myself only when it does not endanger vitally important cooperation.\'94\par
\tab Donald turned toward Caliban. \'93No doubt you are aware a symbolic notational representation of that statement would be remarkably similar to the Second and Third Laws.\'94\par
\tab \'93Similar,\'94 Caliban agreed. \'93But not identical. My version acknowledges the disorderliness of the everyday world--and, I believe, allows me to deal with it more successfully than a Three Law or New Law robot.\'94\par
\tab \'93Enough!\'94 Kresh said. \'93Grieg complained about the Three Laws ruling his life, and I\'92m beginning to see what he meant. Can\'92t we talk about something else?\'94 \par
\tab \'93All right, let\'92s talk about the Control Center, \'93 Fredda said. \'93I don\'92t see how you can choose either the Spacer or Settler design now. Both bids are too badly tainted.\'94\par
\tab \'93I know,\'94 Kresh said. \'93Grieg chose the Spacer design, but I\'92m not so sure he was right to do so. From what I\'92ve been able to see, they\'92re both first-rate designs. The people on both sides were corrupt, but their machinery was fine. I\'92m going to have to think mighty hard about it, but my gut reaction is to build both systems, if we can afford it. I don\'92t quite like the idea of the whole planet\'92s weather being controlled by a robot--or by whoever happens to be pushing the buttons that day on the human-controlled system. If we had both, there would be a system of checks and balances that neither would have on its own. Grieg was a great one for finding a third way. Maybe I can do the same.\'94\par
\tab \'93But what about Grieg\'92s other decision, concerning the New Law robots?\'94 Prospero asked. \'93Will you reverse that decision as well? What\'92s going to happen to us? Will you leave things as they are, or send us to Valhalla--or will it be kingdom come after all?\'94 \par
\tab Donald spoke before Kresh could reply. \'93Sir, I must urge you to consider the danger and chaos the New Law robots have produced. You cannot let it continue. You cannot let them survive.\'94\par
\tab Kresh gave Caliban and Prospero a long look, and then let out a long sigh. \'93Oh, it\'92s tempting,\'94 he said. \'93Very tempting indeed to be rid of you once and for all. But I can\'92t get up and announce to the world that I\'92m scrapping one of Chanto Grieg\'92s most daring experiments. Not when the man isn\'92t cold in his grave yet. I have to let you live, out of respect for his memory. \'94 Kresh was silent for a moment. \'93 And yet Donald is right, too. We can\'92t afford any more of the headaches you New Law types cause. So, damn it all, I suppose it has to be Valhalla,\'94 he said. \par
\tab Prospero bowed slightly and looked Kresh straight in the eye. \'93Thank you, Governor. You have let my people go.\'94\par
\tab The next morning Governor Alvar Kresh and Fredda Leving went out for a stroll in the sunlit grounds of the Winter Residence. The rains were over, a gentle breeze was blowing and there was a fresh-scrubbed feel to the world--a far cry from the dust-choked deserts that surrounded Hades. Nature felt alive and vigorous. The morning, the whole world, seemed full of possibilities. \par
\tab This was how Inferno was supposed to be, Kresh thought. A living world. This is how it\'92s going to be, if I have anything to do with it. Suddenly he felt a sense of purpose stronger than any he had ever felt before. I\'92ll take care of you, he thought, and it was a promise he made to the world of Inferno itself. I will heal you, and make you well. \par
\tab \'93So now it\'92s over,\'94 Fredda said. \'93Or is it?\'94\par
\tab \'93What. The case? There\'92s some tidying up to do, but yes, it\'92s over.\'94\par
\tab \'93There are an awful lot of loose ends to clear up, \'93 Fredda pointed out. \'93We don\'92t know a lot of things about the conspiracy, how exactly it was put together, or how Bissal was recruited, or how and when the SPRs were tampered with.\'94\par
\tab \'93True,\'94 Kresh said. \'93There\'92s a lot of detail work to do, the sort of thing Donald is very good at. Probably I\'92ll put him in charge of it. But in a sense, at least, it is only a question of detail. Tierlaw bought the services of a rustbacking mob, which one, we don\'92t know, but it was almost certainly the one that was paying off Huthwitz. Cinta Melloy almost had them, and she lost them when they got spooked by Grieg\'92s murder. But you found the killer, and I found the mastermind. Working from both ends toward the middle, and with Cinta\'92s leads, we\'92ll roll them up fast enough. Besides, if I pack off the New Laws to Valhalla, there won\'92t be any rustbacking. Once the business collapses and there\'92s no money, there\'92ll be a lot of people ready to talk. We\'92ll get them.\'94\par
\tab \'93You\'92re right, I suppose,\'94 Fredda said. \'93So it is over.\'94\par
\tab \'93And it\'92s just begun,\'94 Kresh said, looking her in the eye. He did not dare say anything more. He was not even sure he knew exactly what he meant--but the way she smiled back at him told him she had understood him precisely. The two of them walked in silence for a time, enjoying the moment, considering the possibilities. \par
\tab \'93It\'92s a beautiful morning,\'94 Fredda said at last. \'93I never expected to see such lovely weather on Purgatory.\'94\par
\tab \'93Nor did I,\'94 Kresh said. \'93But wouldn\'92t this be a fine world if we could expect it?\'94 He stood there for a moment, drinking it all in. But then he turned back, toward the Residence, toward his new duties. \'93Come on, Fredda,\'94 he said, as he reached out and took her by the hand. \'93There\'92s a lot of work for us to do.\'94\par
